export const helpTextEN = {
  incident_date: {
    title: "Why Incident Date Matters for Your Case",
    getContent: (state) => `Understanding when your incident occurred is absolutely critical to determining whether you can pursue legal action. In ${state}, the statute of limitations sets strict deadlines for filing lawsuits, and missing these deadlines means losing your right to compensation forever, regardless of how strong your case may be.

The incident date also affects the calculation of damages in multiple ways. It determines how long you've been suffering from injuries, accumulating medical bills, and losing wages. Additionally, the passage of time can impact the availability and reliability of evidence, witness memories, and documentation. In ${state}, courts consider the timeline of events when assessing the credibility and strength of your claims, making the incident date a foundational element of your case valuation.`
  },

  injury_severity: {
    title: "How Injury Severity Dramatically Impacts Your Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `Injury severity is perhaps the single most important factor in determining your case's financial value. In ${state}, courts and insurance companies evaluate injuries on a spectrum from minor to catastrophic, with each level commanding significantly different compensation ranges. Minor injuries might result in thousands of dollars in damages, while catastrophic injuries can lead to multi-million dollar settlements.

The severity of your injury directly affects multiple categories of damages. Medical expenses increase exponentially with serious injuries, often including emergency care, surgeries, rehabilitation, ongoing treatment, and future medical needs. Lost wages and diminished earning capacity become more substantial with severe injuries that prevent you from working. Most significantly, pain and suffering damages—which ${state} law allows—scale dramatically with injury severity. Insurance adjusters and juries in ${state} consistently award higher compensation for permanent disabilities, disfigurement, and life-altering injuries that require long-term care or adaptive equipment.`
  },

  medical_bills: {
    title: "Why Medical Bills Are the Foundation of Your Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `Medical bills serve as concrete, documentable evidence of the harm you've suffered and represent a major component of your economic damages. In ${state}, courts view medical expenses as objective proof of injury severity and the necessity of treatment. Higher medical bills typically correlate with more serious injuries, which command higher overall case values.

Beyond their face value, medical bills in ${state} influence your case valuation in several ways. They establish a baseline for economic damages that must be compensated. They demonstrate the extent and duration of your treatment, supporting claims for pain and suffering.

${state} law may also allow recovery of future medical expenses, which medical bills help project. Insurance companies use medical bills as a multiplier when calculating settlement offers—often using formulas that multiply medical costs by factors ranging from 1.5 to 5 times depending on injury severity.

Additionally, substantial medical bills can help overcome policy limits and demonstrate to juries the true cost of your injuries, leading to higher verdicts.`
  },

  lost_wages: {
    title: "Understanding How Lost Wages Multiply Your Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `Lost wages represent tangible economic losses that ${state} law entitles you to recover fully. Beyond just the immediate lost income, this component of your case affects your valuation in multiple ways. Courts in ${state} recognize that when injuries prevent you from working, you're not only losing your paycheck—you're potentially losing benefits, career advancement opportunities, and future earning capacity.

The lost wages calculation in ${state} extends beyond simple multiplication of your daily rate by missed days. It includes lost bonuses, commissions, overtime opportunities, and employer-provided benefits like health insurance and retirement contributions.

If your injuries result in permanent disability or reduced working capacity, ${state} law allows recovery for diminished future earnings, which can amount to hundreds of thousands or even millions of dollars over a lifetime.

Insurance companies and defense attorneys closely scrutinize lost wage claims, making documentation crucial. The amount of lost wages also influences pain and suffering multipliers, as significant income loss demonstrates the injury's substantial impact on your life and livelihood in ${state}.`
  },

  annual_income: {
    title: "Why Your Annual Income Is Critical to Calculating Lost Wages",
    getContent: (state) => `Your annual income establishes the baseline for calculating one of the most significant components of your case value—lost wages and diminished earning capacity. In ${state}, courts use your annual income to determine your weekly and daily earning rate, which is then multiplied by the time you were unable to work. Higher annual income directly translates to higher lost wage claims, making this figure crucial to your case valuation.

Beyond just calculating past lost wages, your annual income in ${state} serves several critical purposes. It establishes your earning capacity for future loss calculations, demonstrates the economic value of your time and labor, provides a basis for calculating lost benefits and bonuses, and helps quantify the full economic impact of your injuries.

In ${state}, when injuries result in permanent disability or reduced work capacity, your annual income becomes the foundation for calculating potentially massive future wage loss. For example, a 35-year-old earning $75,000 annually who becomes permanently disabled could have future wage losses exceeding $2 million over their expected work life. Even temporary injuries that prevent work for several months can result in substantial lost wage claims when calculated from a solid annual income baseline.

Insurance companies and defense attorneys will scrutinize your income claims carefully, so accurate documentation is essential. In ${state}, providing tax returns, pay stubs, and employment records to verify your annual income strengthens your case and maximizes your lost wage recovery. Your annual income also influences pain and suffering multipliers, as higher earners often face more significant life disruptions and stress from income loss.`
  },

  weeks_unable_to_work: {
    title: "How Weeks Unable to Work Directly Multiplies Your Compensation",
    getContent: (state) => `The number of weeks you were unable to work provides the precise timeline for calculating your lost wage damages in ${state}. This figure is multiplied by your weekly earning rate to determine your total lost wages—one of the most objective and easily calculable components of your case value. The longer you were unable to work, the higher your lost wage claim and overall case valuation.

In ${state}, the duration of work absence serves multiple important purposes beyond just calculating lost wages. It demonstrates injury severity—longer absences indicate more serious injuries that required extended recovery time. It provides objective evidence of life disruption, showing how significantly the injury impacted your daily functioning. It supports claims for pain and suffering, as extended inability to work proves ongoing disability and limitations.

Extended work absences in ${state} also open the door to additional damages. If you were unable to work for many months, it may indicate potential for future wage loss if you haven't fully recovered. It may show you lost out on promotions, raises, or career advancement opportunities. It can demonstrate the need for vocational rehabilitation if you can't return to your previous occupation.

Insurance adjusters in ${state} pay close attention to this figure because it directly impacts their payout calculations. Documented work absences verified by employer letters and medical records carry significant weight. Even if you used sick leave or vacation time during your recovery, ${state} law typically allows you to recover these as economic losses. The combination of high annual income and extended work absence can result in six-figure lost wage claims, significantly increasing your total case value.`
  },

  fault_percentage: {
    title: "How Fault Percentage Can Make or Break Your Case",
    getContent: (state) => `${state} follows specific fault rules that can dramatically impact your recovery. Understanding fault allocation is critical because even if you're partially responsible for an incident, you may still be entitled to compensation—but the amount can be significantly reduced based on your percentage of fault. This makes the fault determination one of the most heavily contested issues in personal injury cases.

In ${state}, the fault percentage affects not only whether you can recover damages but also how much you'll receive. Defense attorneys and insurance companies aggressively argue for higher fault percentages attributed to victims to reduce their liability.

For example, if your case is worth $100,000 but you're found 30% at fault, your recovery could be reduced to $70,000. The threshold matters too—in some comparative negligence states, if you're found 50% or more at fault, you may recover nothing.

Fault determination in ${state} involves analyzing traffic laws, safety regulations, witness statements, expert testimony, and physical evidence. Every percentage point of fault matters, as it directly translates to money in or out of your pocket. This is why thorough investigation and strong evidence presentation are essential to minimize any fault attributed to you.`
  },

  witness_testimony: {
    title: "Why Witness Testimony Can Double Your Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `Witness testimony serves as powerful independent corroboration of your account of events. In ${state}, cases with credible witness testimony consistently achieve significantly higher settlements and verdicts than cases relying solely on the parties' conflicting accounts. Witnesses provide an objective perspective that judges and juries find highly persuasive, often tipping close cases in favor of the plaintiff.

The presence and quality of witness testimony affects your case value in multiple ways in ${state}. Strong witnesses make defense attorneys more willing to settle and for higher amounts, as they know their chances at trial are reduced. Witnesses can corroborate the severity of impact, your visible injuries at the scene, the defendant's behavior and statements, and environmental conditions.

In ${state} courts, witness credibility is paramount—neutral third-party witnesses (especially professionals or uninvolved bystanders) carry more weight than friends and family. Multiple consistent witnesses create a powerful narrative that's difficult for defense to overcome.

Insurance adjusters use witness availability and credibility as a major factor in their settlement calculations, often applying higher multipliers to cases with strong witness testimony because they understand the increased risk of losing at trial.`
  },

  permanent_disability: {
    title: "Why Permanent Disability Commands Maximum Compensation",
    getContent: (state) => `Permanent disability represents the most serious type of injury outcome and commands the highest compensation in ${state}. When an injury results in permanent disability, you're not just dealing with current damages—you're facing a lifetime of challenges, limitations, and ongoing costs. ${state} law recognizes that permanent disabilities fundamentally alter your life trajectory and entitle you to substantial compensation.

The valuation of permanent disability cases in ${state} is complex and multi-faceted. Beyond current medical bills and lost wages, permanent disability opens the door to substantial future damages including lifetime medical care, ongoing therapy and rehabilitation, adaptive equipment and home modifications, and total loss of earning capacity.

${state} courts also award significantly higher pain and suffering damages for permanent disabilities, recognizing the profound impact on quality of life, relationships, mental health, and daily functioning. Expert testimony from medical specialists, life care planners, and vocational experts becomes essential to fully quantify these damages.

Insurance companies approach permanent disability cases differently, knowing they face potentially catastrophic exposure. Cases involving permanent disability routinely reach six and seven figures in ${state}, with catastrophic permanent disabilities (such as paralysis, traumatic brain injury, or amputation) frequently settling for millions of dollars.`
  },

  police_report: {
    title: "Why a Police Report Strengthens Your Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `A police report serves as an official, contemporaneous record of the incident created by a neutral law enforcement officer. In ${state}, police reports carry significant weight in personal injury cases because they document key facts while memories are fresh and evidence is still available. Insurance companies and courts view police reports as more reliable than after-the-fact recollections, making them powerful tools for establishing liability.

The presence of a police report in ${state} affects your case valuation in several important ways. It provides an official account that typically includes the officer's determination of fault, citations issued, witness statements collected at the scene, and documentation of visible injuries and property damage.

When a police report assigns fault to the other party, it significantly strengthens your position in settlement negotiations, as insurance adjusters know this official determination will be admissible evidence at trial in ${state}. Defense attorneys find it much harder to shift blame or dispute facts when contradicting an official police report.

The report also preserves crucial information that might otherwise be lost, such as the other party's insurance information, witness contact details, and environmental conditions. Cases with police reports supporting the plaintiff's version of events typically settle faster and for higher amounts in ${state}, as they reduce the defendant's ability to create doubt about liability.`
  },

  property_damage: {
    title: "How Property Damage Validates Your Injury Claims",
    getContent: (state) => `Property damage serves as visible, objective evidence of the force and severity of the incident. In ${state}, significant property damage corroborates injury claims by demonstrating the violent nature of the impact. When vehicles are totaled or property is extensively damaged, it becomes much more difficult for defense attorneys and insurance companies to argue that injuries are exaggerated or unrelated to the incident.

The amount and nature of property damage in ${state} influences case valuation beyond just the repair or replacement costs themselves. Substantial property damage supports claims for more serious injuries, as it shows the incident involved significant force. This correlation allows plaintiffs to argue for higher pain and suffering multipliers.

In ${state} courts, photographs and repair estimates of severe property damage create powerful visual evidence that helps juries understand the traumatic nature of the incident. Insurance adjusters use property damage as a factor in their evaluation formulas—cases with severe property damage consistently receive higher injury settlement offers because the physical evidence makes the injury claims more credible.

Additionally, when property damage is extensive, it suggests higher impact speeds or forces, which medical experts can use to explain the mechanism of injury. This objectivity makes property damage documentation one of the strongest tools for maximizing case value in ${state}.`
  },

  treatment_duration: {
    title: "Why Treatment Duration Multiplies Your Compensation",
    getContent: (state) => `The length of your medical treatment directly correlates with case value in ${state}. Extended treatment duration demonstrates injury severity and persistence, showing that your injuries weren't minor or temporary. Insurance companies and courts in ${state} use treatment duration as a key metric when evaluating claims, with longer treatment periods generally commanding substantially higher settlements.

Treatment duration affects your case value in ${state} through multiple channels. First, it increases your total medical bills, which form the foundation of economic damages. Second, it demonstrates ongoing pain and suffering over an extended period, supporting higher non-economic damages. ${state} courts recognize that someone who needed treatment for 12 months suffered far more than someone who recovered in 2 weeks.

Third, lengthy treatment can indicate potential for future medical needs, opening the door to claims for future medical expenses. Fourth, extended treatment often means more time away from work, increasing lost wage claims.

Insurance adjusters in ${state} frequently use treatment duration as a multiplier factor—for example, treating for 6+ months might warrant a 3-4x multiplier on medical bills, while treatment under 3 months might only receive a 1.5-2x multiplier. However, consistency matters: gaps in treatment can be used by defense to argue injuries weren't serious. The key in ${state} is continuous, appropriate treatment that follows medical recommendations and continues until maximum medical improvement is reached.`
  },

  insurance_coverage: {
    title: "How Insurance Coverage Determines Maximum Recovery",
    getContent: (state) => `Insurance coverage limits represent a crucial practical constraint on case value in ${state}. While your actual damages might exceed these limits, the available insurance coverage often determines what you can realistically recover. Understanding policy limits early in your case is essential for setting appropriate expectations and developing effective legal strategy in ${state}.

In ${state}, insurance coverage affects your case in several ways. Policy limits set the maximum amount available from that insurer, meaning even a million-dollar case might only recover $100,000 if that's the policy limit. When damages clearly exceed available coverage, settlement negotiations in ${state} focus on securing the full policy limits.

Multiple insurance policies can stack or layer, potentially increasing total available coverage—for example, the at-fault party's auto policy, their umbrella policy, your underinsured motorist coverage, and other applicable policies. ${state} law governs how these policies interact and whether stacking is permitted.

Understanding available coverage also guides litigation strategy: when coverage is minimal relative to damages, pursuing the insured defendant's personal assets may be necessary, though often impractical. Conversely, when substantial coverage exists, the case has room to reach its full value. Insurance companies in ${state} handle cases differently based on coverage—they fight harder on liability when policy limits are high, knowing they face greater exposure. They may also settle faster for policy limits when damages clearly exceed coverage to avoid bad faith claims.`
  },

  // Additional case-specific questions
  permanent_injury: {
    title: "Why Permanent Injuries Transform Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `Permanent injuries represent life-altering harm that dramatically increases case value in ${state}. Unlike temporary injuries that heal with time, permanent injuries persist indefinitely, affecting every aspect of your life—from daily activities to career opportunities to personal relationships. ${state} law recognizes this profound impact and awards substantially higher compensation for permanent injuries.

When an injury is permanent, your case in ${state} shifts from recovering past damages to accounting for a lifetime of impact. This includes ongoing medical treatment, pain management, therapy, and adaptive equipment for decades. Your earning capacity may be permanently reduced or eliminated, entitling you to recover lost future income.

Pain and suffering damages multiply significantly—${state} courts and juries award much higher amounts when suffering is permanent rather than temporary. Quality of life losses become compensable, including inability to participate in hobbies, sports, family activities, and intimate relationships.

Insurance companies understand that permanent injury cases expose them to potentially catastrophic verdicts in ${state}, making them more willing to negotiate substantial settlements. Expert testimony from medical specialists, vocational experts, and life care planners becomes essential to fully document and quantify the permanent nature and lifetime costs of your injuries.`
  },

  annual_salary: {
    title: "How Your Salary Determines Lost Income Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Your annual salary serves as the foundation for calculating lost income damages in ${state} employment cases. When you've been wrongfully terminated or forced out of employment, your salary establishes the baseline economic loss you've suffered. ${state} courts use salary information to calculate both past lost wages and future lost earning capacity.

In ${state}, your salary affects case valuation beyond simple back pay calculations. Higher salaries result in greater damages for each month of unemployment. Your salary also factors into lost benefits calculations, as benefits packages typically scale with compensation level.

Future earnings calculations in ${state} consider not just your current salary but projected raises, bonuses, and advancement opportunities you've lost. Executive-level positions with six-figure salaries can result in multi-million dollar wrongful termination cases when employment losses extend over years.

Additionally, salary disparities in discrimination cases become powerful evidence of wrongful treatment. ${state} law may also allow recovery of front pay—future salary you would have earned—if reinstatement isn't possible. Documenting your full compensation including bonuses, stock options, and benefits is crucial to maximizing your recovery in ${state} employment cases.`
  },

  emotional_distress: {
    title: "Understanding Emotional Distress Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Emotional distress represents significant non-economic damages that ${state} law allows plaintiffs to recover in many types of cases. Severe emotional distress can be as debilitating as physical injuries, affecting mental health, relationships, work performance, and overall quality of life. ${state} courts recognize that trauma, anxiety, depression, and psychological harm deserve compensation.

The severity of emotional distress in ${state} dramatically affects case value. Mild distress might add modest amounts to settlements, while extreme emotional distress with documented psychiatric treatment, medication, and therapy can increase case value by hundreds of thousands of dollars.

In ${state}, proving emotional distress typically requires evidence such as mental health treatment records, expert testimony from psychologists or psychiatrists, testimony about impact on daily life, and corroboration from family and friends. Cases involving particularly egregious conduct—such as discrimination, civil rights violations, or insurance bad faith—often warrant higher emotional distress damages in ${state}.

When emotional distress reaches the level of diagnosable conditions like PTSD, major depression, or anxiety disorders requiring ongoing treatment, ${state} juries frequently award substantial compensation recognizing the profound and lasting psychological impact of the defendant's conduct.`
  },

  num_dependents: {
    title: "Why Number of Dependents Increases Wrongful Death Value",
    getContent: (state) => `In wrongful death cases in ${state}, the number of dependents significantly affects case valuation because it reflects the scope of financial and emotional loss caused by the death. Each dependent represents a person who relied on the deceased for financial support, guidance, care, and companionship. ${state} law allows recovery for the loss of support and services the deceased would have provided.

The number of dependents in ${state} wrongful death cases impacts multiple damage categories. Each dependent increases the calculated loss of financial support over the victim's expected working life. Young children represent decades of lost support, education funding, and parental guidance.

${state} courts also consider loss of household services—childcare, education assistance, household management—that must now be replaced or compensated. Multiple dependents multiply the loss of consortium and companionship damages, as each family member has suffered an irreplaceable loss.

In ${state}, juries hearing testimony from grieving spouses and children consistently award higher verdicts when they see the breadth of family impact. Additionally, more dependents often means the deceased was in their prime earning years with significant future earning capacity. Cases with multiple minor children routinely reach seven figures in ${state}, as they involve supporting children through adulthood plus the profound emotional loss of parental relationships during crucial developmental years.`
  },

  years_employed: {
    title: "How Length of Employment Affects Your Case",
    getContent: (state) => `Length of employment is a critical factor in ${state} wrongful termination cases, directly affecting both liability findings and damage calculations. Longer employment demonstrates commitment, stability, and presumably satisfactory performance, making wrongful termination claims more credible. ${state} employment law considers tenure when evaluating whether termination was truly for legitimate business reasons or pretextual.

In ${state}, years of employment impact your case value in several ways. Longer tenure often means higher salary and better benefits, increasing economic damages. You may have accumulated significant retirement benefits, stock options, or other deferred compensation that were lost through wrongful termination.

${state} courts and juries view long-term employees more sympathetically—firing someone after 10+ years raises red flags about the employer's justification. Your tenure also affects front pay awards, as ${state} courts consider how much longer you likely would have worked there absent the termination.

Long-time employees may have specialized skills specific to that employer, making replacement employment harder and supporting higher damages. Additionally, age discrimination cases in ${state} become particularly powerful when older, long-tenured employees are replaced by younger workers. The emotional distress of losing a long-term career position where you invested years of your life also warrants higher non-economic damages in ${state} employment litigation.`
  },

  years_relationship: {
    title: "Length of Professional Relationship",
    getContent: (state) => `This field captures how long you worked with the professional who committed malpractice. In ${state}, the length of your professional relationship can demonstrate the degree of reliance and trust you placed in their expertise, which strengthens malpractice claims. Longer relationships also help establish when the malpractice occurred, which is relevant for statute of limitations purposes and proving the professional had sufficient time to recognize and correct errors.`
  },

  unpaid_wages: {
    title: "Understanding Unpaid Wages Claims",
    getContent: (state) => `Unpaid wages represent clear economic damages that ${state} labor law strictly protects. When employers fail to pay wages owed, they violate fundamental employment rights. ${state} wage and hour laws provide robust remedies for workers, often including not just the unpaid wages themselves but also penalties, liquidated damages, interest, and attorney's fees.

In ${state}, unpaid wage claims can escalate quickly. Beyond recovering the actual wages owed, ${state} law may allow recovery of double or treble damages as penalties for wage theft. If multiple pay periods are involved, unpaid wages compound rapidly. Cases involving systematic wage violations affecting multiple employees can become class actions with massive exposure for employers.

${state} courts also recognize that unpaid wages cause significant hardship—inability to pay rent, utilities, food, and other necessities. This strengthens claims for emotional distress damages. Interest accrues on unpaid wages in ${state} from the date they were due.

Additionally, ${state} wage laws often provide for attorney's fee recovery, meaning employers bear the cost of litigation even if the wages owed seem modest. The clear-cut nature of wage claims—either you were paid or you weren't—makes them among the strongest employment claims in ${state}. Documentation through time records, pay stubs, and employment records is crucial to proving the full extent of unpaid wages.`
  },

  unpaid_overtime: {
    title: "Unpaid Overtime Wages",
    getContent: (state) => `This field captures the total overtime wages that should have been paid at the 1.5x rate in ${state}. The Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) requires overtime pay for hours worked over 40 per week for non-exempt employees. Unpaid overtime claims can accumulate substantial damages over time, and ${state} may have additional protections and penalties for wage theft beyond federal requirements, including liquidated damages that can double your recovery.`
  },

  // New questions from analysis
  police_report_filed: {
    title: "Why Police Reports Strengthen Your Motor Vehicle Case",
    getContent: (state) => `A police report provides official, contemporaneous documentation of your accident and serves as powerful independent evidence. In ${state}, police reports are highly persuasive because they're created by neutral third parties with no financial stake in the outcome. Insurance companies and courts give significant weight to police reports when determining liability and evaluating case strength.

Having a police report in ${state} affects your case value in multiple ways. The report documents the scene, road conditions, vehicle damage, visible injuries, and any traffic violations or citations issued. Officers' observations about skid marks, points of impact, and debris patterns help accident reconstruction experts.

Most importantly, when police cite the other driver for violations like running a red light, speeding, or DUI, it creates a strong presumption of fault that's difficult for defense to overcome. ${state} insurance adjusters use police reports as a key factor in settlement calculations, often offering significantly more when reports support your version of events.

Cases without police reports become "he said, she said" disputes where your credibility is constantly challenged. With a police report, you have official corroboration that dramatically strengthens your negotiating position and case value.`
  },

  witnesses_available: {
    title: "How Witnesses Can Double Your Settlement Value",
    getContent: (state) => `Witness testimony transforms your case from a credibility contest into a well-supported claim backed by independent corroboration. In ${state}, the availability of witnesses is one of the strongest predictors of both settlement success and trial verdicts. Witnesses provide an objective perspective that insurance companies and juries find highly persuasive, often making the difference between a modest settlement and maximum compensation.

The impact of witnesses on your ${state} case value is substantial. Defense attorneys know that credible witnesses make their job much harder and increase the risk of losing at trial. This makes them far more willing to settle and for higher amounts. Witnesses can corroborate critical facts: how the accident happened, who was at fault, the severity of impact, your visible pain and injuries at the scene, and the other party's behavior or admissions.

In ${state} courts, neutral third-party witnesses (especially professionals or uninvolved bystanders) carry tremendous weight. Multiple consistent witnesses create a compelling narrative that's nearly impossible to refute.

Insurance adjusters apply higher multipliers to cases with strong witness testimony because they understand the increased litigation risk. Witnesses also deter defense from making lowball offers or engaging in bad faith tactics, as they know the evidence will support you at trial.`
  },

  hospitalized_overnight: {
    title: "Overnight Hospitalization Dramatically Increases Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `Being hospitalized overnight is a critical threshold that signals serious injury severity to insurance companies and juries in ${state}. Emergency room visits where you're sent home the same day suggest minor to moderate injuries. But admission requiring overnight observation or longer stays demonstrates that medical professionals deemed your injuries severe enough to require continuous monitoring and treatment. This single factor can double or triple settlement values.

In ${state}, overnight hospitalization serves as objective proof of injury severity that insurers cannot easily dispute. It generates substantial medical bills, creates detailed hospital records documenting your injuries, and shows clear causation between the accident and your need for intensive medical care. Insurance adjusters use hospitalization as a key metric when evaluating claims—cases with hospital admissions routinely settle for 2-5 times more than similar injuries treated only outpatient.

Hospitalization also strengthens your case for pain and suffering damages. In ${state}, juries understand that hospital stays involve significant trauma, fear, discomfort, and life disruption beyond just the medical treatment. Multi-day stays suggest even more serious injuries like surgeries, broken bones, internal injuries, or traumatic brain injuries—all of which command substantially higher verdicts. Document your hospital stay thoroughly with all discharge papers, bills, and follow-up treatment recommendations.`
  },

  still_in_treatment: {
    title: "Ongoing Treatment Signals Future Medical Costs and Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Still receiving medical treatment months or years after your accident indicates that your injuries haven't fully resolved and you may face ongoing medical expenses and disabilities. In ${state}, current treatment demonstrates that damages are not just past medical bills but include future medical costs that can extend for years or even your lifetime. This transforms case value from tens of thousands to potentially hundreds of thousands or millions for permanent injuries requiring ongoing care.

In ${state}, ongoing treatment is critical for both building your medical record and maximizing damages. Gaps in treatment allow insurers to argue you're not really injured or didn't mitigate damages. But continuous treatment under doctor supervision shows legitimate, persistent injuries that require professional medical management. This supports claims for future medical expenses, permanent disability, reduced earning capacity, and ongoing pain and suffering.

Current treatment also keeps your case "alive" with accumulating damages. In ${state}, you generally cannot settle until reaching maximum medical improvement (MMI)—the point where your condition has stabilized. If you're still improving or undergoing treatment, settling too early means leaving future damages on the table. Ongoing treatment also provides leverage: insurers know that cases with unresolved injuries face higher jury verdicts because future damages add significantly to total exposure.`
  },

  other_driver_insured: {
    title: "Uninsured Drivers Severely Limit Recovery Potential",
    getContent: (state) => `Whether the other driver carries insurance is perhaps the single most important factor determining if you'll actually recover compensation for your injuries in ${state}. Even with a clear-cut liability case and severe injuries, an uninsured driver likely has no meaningful assets to pursue, making your case effectively worthless from a recovery standpoint. This is why this question is critical for evaluating case viability.

In ${state}, roughly 10-15% of drivers operate without insurance despite legal requirements. If the at-fault driver is uninsured, your recovery options are severely limited: you can sue them personally, but most uninsured drivers lack assets to satisfy judgments. You may have uninsured motorist (UM) coverage through your own policy—check your policy immediately. UM coverage allows you to pursue compensation from your own insurer when the at-fault driver lacks insurance.

If the other driver is insured, your case becomes viable for full compensation. You can file a claim against their liability policy, which in ${state} carries minimum limits (though these are often inadequate for serious injuries). Insurance companies have both the ability and legal obligation to pay valid claims. If the at-fault driver is insured but carries only minimum limits, you may still recover additional compensation through your own underinsured motorist (UIM) coverage. Always verify the other driver's insurance status immediately after an accident—this determines whether pursuing your case makes financial sense.`
  },

  filed_eeoc_complaint: {
    title: "EEOC Complaints Establish Legal Standing and Seriousness",
    getContent: (state) => `Filing an EEOC (Equal Employment Opportunity Commission) complaint or state equivalent is often a prerequisite for pursuing federal discrimination claims in ${state}. More importantly, it demonstrates to employers, insurers, and courts that you're serious about your claims and willing to pursue formal legal channels. EEOC complaints create official government records of your allegations, establish timelines that support your case, and often trigger higher settlement offers because employers understand you're prepared for litigation.

In ${state}, EEOC complaints serve multiple strategic purposes. First, they're legally required before filing federal lawsuits under Title VII, ADA, or ADEA for most employment discrimination claims. The EEOC investigates, attempts conciliation, and issues a "right to sue" letter if settlement fails. Second, EEOC involvement signals to employers that you have legal guidance and understand your rights. Third, the complaint creates a formal record with specific allegations that employers must respond to, preventing them from changing their story later.

EEOC complaints also dramatically increase settlement leverage. Employers know that EEOC involvement often leads to litigation, discovery, and potential exposure of broader company-wide discrimination patterns. In ${state}, employers facing EEOC complaints routinely settle for higher amounts to avoid the costs and risks of federal litigation. Even if the EEOC doesn't find cause, your right-to-sue letter allows you to proceed in court, and the investigation often uncovers additional evidence supporting your claims.`
  },

  have_termination_docs: {
    title: "Documentation Proves Your Case and Prevents Employer Lies",
    getContent: (state) => `Having written documentation of your termination—termination letters, emails, performance reviews, disciplinary notices, or witness statements—is crucial for proving wrongful termination in ${state}. Documentation transforms "he said, she said" disputes into concrete evidence that employers cannot easily refute. Written records lock employers into specific justifications for termination, preventing them from changing their story later to avoid liability.

In ${state}, termination documentation serves multiple critical functions. First, it proves the termination actually occurred and when—important for statute of limitations. Second, it captures the employer's stated reasons for termination in real time, before they consult with lawyers and craft more defensible explanations. Third, inconsistencies between termination documents and later sworn testimony can prove pretext and bad faith, strengthening discrimination or retaliation claims.

Documentation also dramatically increases settlement values because it reduces employer defenses and litigation risks. In ${state}, employers facing strong documentary evidence that contradicts their defenses know they're likely to lose at trial. Termination emails showing discriminatory animus, performance reviews proving you were meeting expectations, or communications revealing retaliation all create devastating proof that forces higher settlements. Always request written documentation of termination reasons, save all work emails and reviews, and document conversations through follow-up emails. Cases with strong documentation routinely settle for 2-3 times more than cases relying solely on testimony.`
  },

  victim_age: {
    title: "How Victim's Age Affects Wrongful Death Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `The victim's age is fundamental to calculating economic damages in wrongful death cases because it determines life expectancy and potential future earnings. In ${state}, younger victims generally have longer life expectancies, meaning more years of lost income, companionship, and support. Courts use actuarial tables and the victim's age to project decades of future earnings that must be compensated to surviving family members.

Age affects ${state} wrongful death valuations in complex ways. A victim in their prime earning years (30s-50s) typically has the highest economic value due to peak income and many working years ahead. Younger victims may have less established earnings but longer life expectancy, while older victims may have reached peak earnings but fewer remaining years.

${state} law also considers the impact on dependents—young children losing a parent face decades without that parent's financial support, guidance, and presence. Non-economic damages also vary with age: a spouse losing their life partner has different loss of companionship claims than adult children losing an elderly parent.

The victim's age influences jury sympathy as well—untimely deaths of those in their prime often generate larger verdicts. Accurately assessing age-based life expectancy is crucial for properly valuing the full extent of economic and non-economic losses in ${state} wrongful death cases.`
  },

  relationship_to_victim: {
    title: "Why Your Relationship to the Victim Matters",
    getContent: (state) => `Your relationship to the victim directly determines your legal standing to bring a wrongful death claim and significantly affects the damages you can recover. In ${state}, wrongful death statutes specify which family members can sue and prioritize certain relationships. The closer and more dependent your relationship, the stronger your claim for both economic and emotional damages.

In ${state}, spouses typically have the strongest wrongful death claims due to loss of financial support, consortium, companionship, and household services. Children (especially minor or dependent children) can claim loss of parental guidance, support, and nurturing. Parents who lost adult children may have more limited economic claims but strong emotional distress claims.

${state} courts evaluate the nature and quality of the relationship—were you financially dependent on the victim? Did you live together? How close was your emotional bond? These factors affect jury awards for non-economic damages like loss of companionship and emotional suffering.

The relationship also influences settlement negotiations, as insurance companies assess which family members have the most compelling claims. Understanding your relationship to the victim helps properly frame your damages and ensures you recover full compensation for your specific losses under ${state} wrongful death law.`
  },

  conscious_pain_suffering: {
    title: "Conscious Pain and Suffering Before Death",
    getContent: (state) => `When a victim experiences conscious pain and suffering between the injury and death, ${state} law recognizes this as a separate, compensable harm known as "survival damages." This is distinct from wrongful death damages and represents the victim's own suffering that the estate can recover. Conscious pain and suffering before death significantly increases the total case value.

In ${state}, conscious pain and suffering damages compensate for the victim's physical pain, emotional distress, fear, and awareness of impending death during their final moments, hours, or days. These damages can be substantial—even brief periods of conscious suffering command significant compensation.

${state} courts and juries are particularly moved by evidence that the victim was aware of what was happening, experienced terror or anguish, or suffered severe pain before dying. Medical records, first responder testimony, and witness accounts documenting the victim's conscious state are crucial. The duration matters, but even moments of conscious suffering warrant damages.

In ${state}, survival claims may also include the victim's medical expenses and lost earnings from injury to death. The combination of wrongful death damages (for the family's losses) and survival damages (for the victim's own suffering) can dramatically increase the total recovery in cases where the victim endured conscious pain before death.`
  },

  dog_prior_aggression: {
    title: "Prior Aggression History Increases Your Dog Bite Case",
    getContent: (state) => `A dog's history of prior aggression or attacks is critical evidence that dramatically strengthens your case and increases damages. In ${state}, prior aggression shows the owner knew or should have known their dog was dangerous, establishing negligence and potentially warranting punitive damages. This transforms your case from a simple negligence claim into one involving reckless endangerment.

Prior aggression affects your ${state} dog bite case in multiple ways. Many states impose strict liability for dog bites, but prior attacks strengthen your claim regardless of liability standard. Evidence that the dog previously bit, lunged at, or threatened people or animals proves the owner had knowledge of the danger and failed to take adequate precautions.

${state} courts view owners who ignore warning signs as particularly culpable. Prior incidents also help overcome defenses like "the dog was provoked" or "this was completely out of character." Insurance companies recognize that prior aggression makes their case much weaker and increases jury appeal, leading to higher settlements.

In ${state}, prior attacks may support punitive damages claims if the owner's conduct was especially reckless. Document any evidence of prior incidents: animal control reports, veterinary records noting aggressive behavior, witness statements from neighbors or previous victims, or the owner's own admissions about the dog's temperament.`
  },

  facial_injuries: {
    title: "Why Facial Injuries Command Highest Dog Bite Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Facial injuries from dog bites are among the most serious and highly compensated injuries in ${state} personal injury law. The face is central to personal identity, social interaction, and self-image. Facial scarring, disfigurement, or permanent changes to appearance cause profound psychological trauma beyond the physical injury itself, warranting substantially higher damage awards.

In ${state}, facial injuries dramatically increase dog bite case values for several reasons. Facial injuries typically require extensive medical treatment: emergency care, plastic surgery, reconstructive procedures, and often multiple revision surgeries over years. The visible, permanent nature of facial scarring makes damages obvious to juries, unlike injuries hidden under clothing.

${state} law recognizes distinct damages for disfigurement and loss of enjoyment of life—facial injuries directly impact social relationships, employment prospects, and psychological well-being. Victims of facial scarring often experience depression, anxiety, social withdrawal, and PTSD. Children with facial injuries face a lifetime of explaining their scars and potential bullying.

Insurance companies understand facial injury cases have extraordinary jury appeal and typically command premiums over other injuries. In ${state}, facial dog bite cases frequently settle for several times the typical dog bite case value, with severe facial disfigurement cases reaching six figures or more.`
  },

  violation_type: {
    title: "How Violation Type Affects Civil Rights Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `The specific type of civil rights violation significantly impacts your case's strength, available remedies, and potential damages. In ${state}, certain violations—like police excessive force or employment discrimination—have well-established legal frameworks and precedents, while others involve developing areas of law. The nature of your violation determines which statutes apply, what you must prove, and how much you can recover.

Different civil rights violations in ${state} command different damage ranges. Police excessive force cases often result in large verdicts due to clear constitutional violations and § 1983 remedies. False arrest cases have substantial damages especially with prolonged detention. Employment discrimination provides both compensatory and punitive damages under federal law. Housing discrimination violations carry statutory minimums.

First Amendment cases protecting free speech are highly fact-specific. ${state} courts have developed expertise in certain civil rights areas, creating predictable damage ranges. Juries respond emotionally to certain violations—police brutality cases especially involving video evidence generate outrage and large verdicts.

The violation type also determines whether punitive damages are available and how much. Understanding your specific violation type helps properly frame your case, cite relevant precedents, and pursue maximum recovery under ${state} and federal civil rights laws.`
  },

  video_evidence: {
    title: "Why Video Evidence Is Game-Changing in Civil Rights Cases",
    getContent: (state) => `Video evidence has revolutionized civil rights litigation and consistently leads to dramatically higher settlements and verdicts. In ${state}, video removes the credibility battle inherent in most cases and provides irrefutable proof of what actually happened. Insurance companies and government entities recognize that video evidence makes cases nearly impossible to defend, leading to quicker and larger settlements.

Video evidence affects ${state} civil rights cases in powerful ways. It eliminates "he said, she said" disputes where officials' testimony would otherwise prevail. Videos capture objective facts: the level of force used, whether you posed a threat, official misconduct, false statements by officers, and your visible injuries and distress.

In ${state} courts, juries watching video of civil rights violations react viscerally, often awarding substantial damages based on what they witness. Video also prevents defense tactics like victim-blaming or justifying excessive force. Body cam footage, surveillance videos, and cell phone recordings all serve as powerful evidence.

Social media can amplify your case, creating public pressure for accountability. In ${state}, civil rights cases with video evidence routinely settle for multiples of similar cases without video. Video makes the violation undeniable and transforms your negotiating position.`
  },

  physical_injury: {
    title: "Physical Injury in Civil Rights Cases",
    getContent: (state) => `Physical injury in civil rights cases transforms your claim from a pure constitutional violation into one with concrete, demonstrable harm. In ${state}, physical injuries provide objective evidence of the violation's severity and significantly increase both compensatory and punitive damages. Courts and juries view physical injuries as proof that the rights violation had real, painful consequences beyond abstract constitutional concerns.

Physical injury affects ${state} civil rights valuations dramatically. While constitutional violations alone warrant damages, physical injuries add substantial medical expenses, pain and suffering, and lost wages to your recovery. The severity matters—bruises and minor injuries strengthen your case, while broken bones, head trauma, or permanent injuries can lead to six or seven-figure verdicts in ${state}.

Physical injuries also make punitive damages more likely, as they demonstrate the defendant's conduct crossed the line from mere rights violations to physical harm. In excessive force cases, your injuries directly prove the force was unreasonable. Physical injuries also create powerful jury appeal—injuries from government abuse generate outrage and sympathy.

Document all injuries through medical records, photographs, and expert testimony. In ${state}, civil rights cases with physical injuries consistently achieve substantially higher settlements than cases without physical harm.`
  },

  positive_performance_reviews: {
    title: "Performance Reviews Prove Wrongful Termination",
    getContent: (state) => `Positive performance reviews are powerful evidence that your termination was pretextual rather than for legitimate business reasons. In ${state} employment law, when employers claim termination was for poor performance but your reviews were positive, this contradiction strongly suggests discrimination, retaliation, or other unlawful motives. Performance reviews serve as the employer's own admission that you were a good employee.

In ${state}, positive performance reviews affect wrongful termination cases significantly. They directly contradict performance-based termination justifications, exposing them as pretexts. When employers can't point to documented performance issues, courts and juries infer unlawful motive.

This pattern is common: positive reviews followed by sudden termination after reporting harassment, taking FMLA leave, or engaging in protected activity. ${state} courts recognize this as evidence of unlawful retaliation. Positive reviews also increase your economic damages—they demonstrate you likely would have remained employed long-term, supporting larger front pay awards.

They show you were a valued employee, making the emotional distress of wrongful termination more severe. In settlement negotiations, positive performance reviews dramatically strengthen your position, as employers know juries won't believe sudden performance-based terminations contradict years of positive evaluations. Always preserve performance reviews, raises, bonuses, and promotions as evidence of your strong work history.`
  },

  position_filled: {
    title: "Position Being Filled Proves Pretext",
    getContent: (state) => `When an employer quickly fills your position after claiming termination was due to downsizing, restructuring, or elimination of your role, this is powerful evidence of pretextual discrimination or retaliation. In ${state} employment law, employers who claim legitimate business reasons for termination but then fill the position—especially with someone outside your protected class—face strong inference of unlawful motive.

Position-filling evidence affects ${state} wrongful termination cases substantially. It directly contradicts common defenses: "We had to eliminate the position" or "Restructuring made your role redundant." When the position is filled immediately, these justifications are exposed as lies.

This is especially powerful in age discrimination cases when older employees are replaced by younger workers, or gender/race discrimination when replaced by someone of different demographics. ${state} courts view position-filling as strong circumstantial evidence of discrimination. The timing matters—immediate replacement is more suspicious than eventually hiring someone months later for a different role.

Position-filling also affects damages: it proves the employer had continuing need for your work, supporting claims for future lost wages. In negotiations, evidence that they filled your position dramatically strengthens your leverage, as employers know juries will see through the pretextual justification. Track the position after termination through LinkedIn, company websites, and job postings.`
  },

  insurance_type: {
    title: "Insurance Type Affects Bad Faith Case Value",
    getContent: (state) => `The type of insurance policy involved significantly impacts bad faith case values and available remedies. In ${state}, different insurance types have different bad faith standards, statutory protections, and damage potentials. Health and disability insurance bad faith cases often result in higher damages than auto or homeowners claims due to the severe impact of delayed or denied medical coverage.

Insurance type affects ${state} bad faith valuations in multiple ways. Health insurance denials can involve life-threatening conditions, creating substantial emotional distress and potential for punitive damages. Disability insurance cases involve extended periods of no income, creating severe financial hardship. Life insurance denials devastate beneficiaries during grief. ${state} courts and juries are particularly sympathetic to bad faith in these critical areas.

Different insurance types also have different regulatory frameworks—health insurance has strong consumer protections, ERISA governs many disability policies with different rules. The underlying claim value matters: homeowners bad faith over a $300,000 house fire claim has more exposure than auto bad faith over a $5,000 claim.

In ${state}, certain insurance types have specific bad faith statutes with statutory penalties, treble damages, or mandatory attorney fees. Understanding your insurance type helps frame your bad faith claim properly and pursue maximum damages under applicable ${state} law.`
  },

  multiple_denials: {
    title: "Multiple Denials Prove Insurance Bad Faith",
    getContent: (state) => `When an insurance company denies your claim multiple times—especially after appeals or additional evidence—this pattern strongly suggests bad faith rather than mere coverage disputes. In ${state}, multiple denials demonstrate the insurer's unwillingness to fairly evaluate your claim and may support punitive damages for intentional misconduct or oppressive conduct.

Multiple denials affect ${state} bad faith cases powerfully. A single denial might be explained as a coverage dispute or mistake, but repeated denials despite compelling evidence shows deliberate refusal to pay valid claims. This pattern is especially egregious when you submit additional medical evidence, expert opinions, or documentation supporting your claim, yet the insurer keeps finding new reasons to deny.

${state} courts view multiple denials as evidence of systematic bad faith, not good faith coverage disputes. Each denial compounds your damages—extending your time without benefits, increasing financial hardship, and escalating emotional distress. Multiple denials also suggest the insurer is trying to exhaust you into giving up rather than honestly evaluating your claim.

In ${state}, this conduct may warrant punitive damages designed to punish and deter such behavior. Document each denial carefully, noting shifting justifications, ignored evidence, and the impact of prolonged denial on your finances and wellbeing. Multiple denials dramatically strengthen your bad faith case and increase potential recovery.`
  },

  hazard_type: {
    title: "Hazard Type Determines Premises Liability Value",
    getContent: (state) => `The specific type of hazard that caused your injury significantly affects premises liability case values. In ${state}, certain hazards—like inadequate security or structural failures—suggest particularly egregious negligence, while slip-and-falls face more defense challenges. The hazard type determines what duty of care the property owner owed and how obvious their negligence was.

Different hazards affect ${state} premises cases differently. Inadequate security cases (assaults, robberies) often result in high verdicts when property owners ignored known crime problems, especially if victims suffered violent attacks. Structural failures (collapsing stairs, railings, balconies) suggest obvious maintenance failures and create strong liability. Falling object cases depend on whether the property owner had notice.

Slip-and-falls face scrutiny over whether the hazard was "open and obvious" and whether you were paying attention. Trip hazards require showing the property owner created or knew about the condition.

In ${state}, certain hazards invoke specific premises liability standards: inadequate security cases must show foreseeability of crime, while dangerous condition cases require proving notice. The hazard type also affects damages—violent crimes from inadequate security cause severe trauma and high damages, while simple slips may result in less serious injuries. Understanding your specific hazard type helps frame your ${state} premises case properly and overcome common defenses.`
  },

  commercial_property: {
    title: "Commercial Properties Have Higher Duty of Care",
    getContent: (state) => `Injuries occurring on commercial properties generally result in stronger premises liability cases and higher damages than residential injuries. In ${state}, commercial property owners and businesses owe customers a higher duty of care due to their invitation onto the property for business purposes. Commercial entities also typically have better insurance coverage and deeper pockets for satisfying judgments.

Commercial property status affects ${state} premises cases substantially. Business invitees receive the highest protection under ${state} premises law—owners must actively inspect for hazards and warn of or remedy dangerous conditions. Commercial property owners are held to professional standards: regular inspections, maintenance protocols, and safety procedures.

Violations of building codes or safety regulations create strong negligence claims. ${state} courts recognize commercial entities have resources to maintain safe premises and experience managing customer safety. Commercial properties also face higher financial exposure—businesses understand premises liability risk and carry substantial insurance for customer injuries, often millions in coverage.

This affects settlement negotiations, as insurance companies know commercial property liability cases have strong jury appeal. Juries hold businesses to high safety standards and award larger damages against commercial defendants than private homeowners. Commercial status also enables discovery of prior incidents, inspection records, and safety policy violations that strengthen your case in ${state}.`
  },

  professional_fees_paid: {
    title: "Professional Fees Paid",
    getContent: (state) => `This field captures the total fees you paid to the professional (attorney, accountant, financial advisor, etc.) before discovering the malpractice. In ${state}, this establishes the professional relationship and demonstrates your reliance on their expertise. These fees can often be recovered as damages if you prove the services were negligently performed, as you paid for competent professional advice but received substandard work that caused you harm.`
  },

  professional_type: {
    title: "How Professional Type Affects Malpractice Cases",
    getContent: (state) => `The type of professional who committed malpractice significantly affects case values, applicable standards of care, and damage calculations. In ${state}, different professionals face different malpractice standards, insurance requirements, and typical damage ranges. Attorney and accountant malpractice often involves larger financial stakes than other professional malpractice types.

Professional type affects ${state} malpractice cases in multiple ways. Attorney malpractice cases involve "case within a case" analysis—proving you would have won but for the attorney's negligence. These can result in substantial damages if the underlying case was valuable. Accountant malpractice may involve tax liabilities, audit failures, or business financial harm, potentially reaching millions in large business contexts.

Financial advisor malpractice depends on investment losses and duty violations, with damages based on account values. Architect and engineer malpractice involves construction defects or design failures, potentially affecting property values significantly. Real estate agent malpractice typically involves disclosure failures or contractual breaches with damages tied to property values.

Each profession has specific standards of care and practice requirements in ${state}. Insurance coverage varies—attorneys typically carry substantial malpractice insurance, while some professions have lower coverage limits. Understanding your professional's type helps identify relevant standards of care, expert witnesses in that field, and realistic damage expectations under ${state} professional malpractice law.`
  },

  policy_type: {
    title: "Policy Type Determines Disability Claim Value",
    getContent: (state) => `The type of disability policy you have fundamentally affects your claim's value, legal standards, and available remedies. In ${state}, employer-sponsored group plans governed by ERISA face different rules than individual policies, social security has its own procedures, and veterans disability follows VA standards. Understanding your policy type is crucial for properly pursuing your claim.

Policy type affects ${state} disability cases dramatically. ERISA-governed employer group plans have significant restrictions: no jury trials, no punitive damages, and limited discovery. However, you can recover attorney fees if you win. Individual disability policies are governed by state law, allowing jury trials, broader discovery, and potential punitive damages for bad faith—often resulting in larger recoveries.

Social Security disability has administrative procedures and strict medical requirements, with benefits set by federal tables. Veterans disability through VA has separate appeals processes and compensation schedules.

In ${state}, individual policies offer better recovery potential than ERISA plans because you can pursue bad faith claims with full damages. Policy type also affects the definition of "disability"—some require inability to perform any occupation, others your own occupation. Understanding these distinctions is critical for framing your claim, choosing proper legal strategies, and setting realistic damage expectations. The policy type may be the single most important factor in determining your disability case strategy in ${state}.`
  },

  appeal_denied: {
    title: "Appeal Denial Strengthens Disability Bad Faith Claims",
    getContent: (state) => `When an insurance company denies your disability appeal, it demonstrates a pattern of refusing valid claims and strengthens bad faith allegations. In ${state}, appeals require insurers to carefully review additional evidence and medical documentation. Denial after a thorough appeal suggests the insurer is not acting in good faith but rather looking for any excuse to avoid paying legitimate claims.

Appeal denial affects ${state} disability cases significantly. A denial after appeal shows the insurer maintained its position even when confronted with additional medical evidence, expert opinions, or documentation. This pattern suggests bad faith—especially when the appeal included strong supporting evidence that any reasonable insurer would accept.

Appeal denial extends the time you've been without benefits, compounding financial hardship and emotional distress. In ${state}, multiple levels of denial (initial claim, first appeal, second appeal) create an increasingly strong case for bad faith. Appeal denials also often expose inconsistencies or contradictory explanations, as insurers sometimes change their reasons for denial across different stages.

This undermines their credibility and suggests pretextual justifications. Denied appeals may support punitive damages if the pattern shows willful disregard for valid claims. In settlement negotiations, appeal denial dramatically increases your leverage, as insurers know continued refusal to pay appears indefensible. Carefully document each appeal with all supporting evidence to show the insurer's unreasonable denial pattern in ${state}.`
  },

  ip_type: {
    title: "IP Type Determines Infringement Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `The type of intellectual property infringed—patent, trademark, copyright, or trade secret—fundamentally determines available remedies, damage calculations, and case values. In ${state}, each IP type has distinct federal or state law frameworks, different damage formulas, and varying potential for enhanced damages. Understanding your IP type is crucial for properly valuing and pursuing your infringement claim.

IP type affects ${state} infringement cases dramatically. Patent infringement offers some of the highest damages, including reasonable royalties or lost profits, with potential for willful infringement treble damages and attorney fees. Patents protect valuable innovations, and damages can reach millions for significant commercial patents.

Copyright infringement allows either actual damages or statutory damages ($750-$30,000 per work, up to $150,000 if willful), making copyright particularly valuable for multiple infringements. Trademark infringement focuses on profits from infringement plus actual damages, with potential trebling for willfulness. Trade secret misappropriation under ${state} law or the federal DTSA provides compensatory damages and potential punitive damages for willful theft.

Each IP type has different proof requirements and defenses. Copyright and trademark registration requirements affect remedy availability. Patent cases are technically complex and expensive to litigate. In ${state}, the IP type determines whether you proceed in federal or state court, what experts you need, and realistic settlement ranges. Strong registered IP rights typically command higher settlements than unregistered rights due to presumed validity.`
  },

  class_action_type: {
    title: "Class Action Type Determines Case Scope",
    getContent: (state) => `The specific type of class action dramatically affects case values, litigation complexity, and settlement potential. In ${state}, different class action types—data breaches, consumer fraud, defective products, securities fraud, or employment violations—involve different laws, damage calculations, and typical settlement ranges. The class action type determines the legal framework, class certification requirements, and potential exposure for defendants.

Class action type affects ${state} cases in fundamental ways. Data breach class actions often involve statutory damages per violation, potentially creating massive exposure when thousands or millions of consumers are affected. Consumer fraud cases may involve treble damages under consumer protection laws. Defective product cases combine personal injury claims with economic losses for all purchasers.

Securities fraud follows federal securities laws with damages tied to stock price declines and investor losses. Employment class actions involve systematic wage theft, discrimination, or misclassification affecting many workers.

In ${state}, each type has different class certification standards—data breach plaintiffs must show actual harm, while consumer fraud cases focus on common questions of law. Settlement values vary tremendously: small individual harms across large classes can settle for millions, while serious personal injuries in product defect classes might settle for tens or hundreds of millions. The class action type determines whether federal or ${state} courts hear the case, what defenses apply, and realistic damage ranges. Understanding your class action type is essential for proper case valuation and litigation strategy.`
  },

  surgery_error: {
    title: "Why Surgery Errors Command Highest Medical Malpractice Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Surgery errors represent some of the most serious medical malpractice cases and typically result in the highest damage awards. In ${state}, surgical mistakes are often considered "never events"—errors so egregious they should never occur with proper care. Wrong-site surgery, retained surgical instruments, anesthesia errors, and surgical technique failures demonstrate clear deviations from the standard of care.

Surgery errors affect ${state} medical malpractice valuations dramatically. These cases often involve catastrophic permanent injuries requiring additional corrective surgeries, extended recovery, and lifelong complications. The clear-cut nature of many surgery errors—operating on the wrong body part, leaving instruments inside patients, or damaging organs—makes liability easier to prove than diagnostic errors.

${state} juries react strongly to surgery errors because they violate the fundamental trust patients place in surgeons. Expert testimony powerfully demonstrates how these errors deviate from basic surgical protocols. Surgery error cases frequently support punitive damages when the error stems from recklessness, such as operating while impaired or ignoring safety checklists.

Economic damages accumulate rapidly: the original surgery costs, corrective procedures, extended disability, and permanent complications. Non-economic damages for pain, suffering, and loss of quality of life are substantial. In ${state}, surgery error cases routinely reach six or seven figures, with catastrophic errors settling for millions of dollars.`
  },

  property_owner_warned: {
    title: "Prior Warnings Prove Property Owner Negligence",
    getContent: (state) => `Evidence that a property owner was warned about a dangerous condition before your injury is extraordinarily powerful in premises liability cases. In ${state}, prior warnings establish the owner had actual knowledge of the hazard and failed to remedy it, transforming your case from one of potential constructive notice to clear actual notice. This dramatically strengthens liability and often supports punitive damages for willful negligence.

Property owner warnings affect ${state} premises cases powerfully. When you can prove the owner received prior complaints, incident reports, inspection notices, or warnings from tenants, customers, or authorities, it eliminates the owner's defense that they didn't know about the hazard. Prior warnings show not just knowledge but continued inaction despite awareness of the danger.

This is especially powerful in inadequate security cases where prior crimes put owners on notice, slip-and-fall cases with repeated complaints, and structural defect cases with ignored maintenance requests. ${state} courts view warned property owners as particularly culpable—they knew people were at risk but prioritized cost savings over safety.

Prior warnings also support higher damages because they demonstrate the preventable nature of your injuries. Document all evidence of warnings: complaint logs, maintenance requests, inspection reports, prior incident reports, emails, or letters warning the owner. In ${state}, proof of prior warnings can double or triple case values and may warrant punitive damages to punish and deter such negligent conduct.`
  },

  scarring: {
    title: "Permanent Scarring Increases Case Value Substantially",
    getContent: (state) => `Permanent scarring represents visible, lasting disfigurement that significantly increases case values beyond the underlying injury. In ${state}, scars affect your appearance, self-image, social interactions, and emotional well-being for life. Courts and juries recognize that permanent scarring causes ongoing psychological harm and awards substantial compensation for disfigurement separate from other injuries.

Scarring affects ${state} personal injury valuations in multiple ways. Visible scars on the face, neck, arms, or legs have greater impact than scars hidden under clothing. Large, disfiguring scars command higher damages than small marks. Scarring that affects young people or children is particularly tragic, as they face a lifetime of explaining their scars and potential social stigma.

In ${state}, scarring damages account for both the physical mark and the emotional distress, self-consciousness, and depression it causes. Scarring may require additional treatment including scar revision surgery, laser treatment, or cosmetic procedures to minimize appearance. Even with treatment, most scars never completely disappear.

${state} juries seeing photographs of significant scarring typically award substantial damages recognizing the permanent nature of disfigurement. Scarring can affect employment opportunities, romantic relationships, and daily self-confidence. In ${state}, cases with permanent visible scarring routinely command premiums of $50,000 to $500,000 or more beyond other injury damages, depending on scar location, size, and severity.`
  },

  victim_annual_income: {
    title: "Victim's Income Determines Economic Loss in Wrongful Death",
    getContent: (state) => `The victim's annual income is fundamental to calculating economic damages in wrongful death cases because it establishes the financial support lost to surviving family members. In ${state}, courts project the victim's future earnings over their expected working life to determine the total economic loss. Higher earners create larger economic damage awards, as their death represents greater lost financial support.

Victim income affects ${state} wrongful death valuations substantially. Economic damages include not just current salary but projected raises, bonuses, benefits, and career advancement. A victim earning $100,000 annually with 30 years of expected working life represents $3 million or more in lost earnings before adjusting for present value.

${state} courts consider the victim's age, occupation, education, health, and career trajectory when projecting future income. Young professionals with high earning potential may have the highest economic damages despite current modest salaries. Income also includes employment benefits: health insurance, retirement contributions, stock options, and other compensation.

Lost household services—childcare, maintenance, financial management—add to economic damages. In ${state}, expert economists testify about lifetime earning capacity, creating detailed projections that support multi-million dollar damage awards for high earners. Even modest incomes accumulate to substantial damages over decades. Accurately documenting the victim's income, benefits, and career prospects is crucial for maximizing wrongful death recovery in ${state}.`
  },

  funeral_costs: {
    title: "Funeral Costs Are Immediately Recoverable Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Funeral and burial expenses represent concrete economic damages that ${state} law allows surviving family members to recover in wrongful death cases. These costs are immediately calculable and undeniable, providing a baseline for economic damages. While funeral costs alone may be modest compared to total damages, they represent real financial burdens that wrongful death compensation must address.

Funeral costs in ${state} wrongful death cases typically include burial or cremation, casket or urn, funeral home services, cemetery plot, headstone or marker, death certificates, transportation, flowers, and memorial services. These expenses can easily exceed $10,000 to $20,000 or more.

In ${state}, funeral cost recovery is straightforward—present receipts and invoices documenting actual expenses incurred. Unlike pain and suffering damages that require valuation, funeral costs are concrete and non-controversial. They also humanize your case, reminding juries that your family faced immediate financial hardship on top of devastating emotional loss.

Some ${state} families incur additional costs for elaborate memorials, mausoleums, or culturally significant burial practices, which may be recoverable depending on reasonableness. Pre-existing funeral insurance or assistance may offset some costs but doesn't eliminate the defendant's liability. Funeral costs also start accumulating damages immediately, while other economic losses like lost income must be projected. Document all funeral-related expenses carefully to ensure full recovery in your ${state} wrongful death claim.`
  },

  child_victim: {
    title: "Child Victims Command Highest Wrongful Death Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Wrongful death cases involving child victims are among the most emotionally devastating and legally significant cases, typically resulting in the highest damage awards. In ${state}, losing a child represents an unnatural tragedy that profoundly impacts parents and family members. Juries respond with enormous sympathy, and courts recognize the unique nature of parental loss of a child.

Child victim cases affect ${state} wrongful death valuations in powerful ways. While children may have no established earnings, ${state} law allows recovery for lost future earnings based on educational trajectory and earning potential. A child who would have completed college and entered a professional career represents decades of potential earnings.

More importantly, child wrongful death cases emphasize non-economic damages: the loss of companionship, affection, guidance, and the joy of watching the child grow. Parents losing children suffer unique grief that ${state} juries recognize deserves substantial compensation. The unnatural order of parents outliving children creates profound emotional trauma.

Children also have longer life expectancies, meaning families lost more years of companionship than losing an elderly family member. In ${state}, child wrongful death cases routinely result in multi-million dollar verdicts even without substantial economic damages, as juries attempt to compensate parents for their immeasurable loss. Defense attorneys understand child victim cases have extraordinary jury appeal and typically recommend substantial settlements to avoid even higher jury verdicts.`
  },

  discrimination: {
    title: "Discrimination Claims Transform Wrongful Termination Values",
    getContent: (state) => `When wrongful termination involves illegal discrimination based on protected characteristics like age, race, gender, disability, or religion, case values increase dramatically. In ${state}, discrimination claims add federal and state law claims beyond simple wrongful termination, opening the door to compensatory and punitive damages, emotional distress recovery, and attorney fee awards that transform case values.

Discrimination affects ${state} employment cases fundamentally. Federal laws (Title VII, ADEA, ADA) and ${state} anti-discrimination statutes provide remedies beyond common law wrongful termination: back pay, front pay, emotional distress damages, and punitive damages up to statutory caps (often $50,000 to $300,000 depending on employer size). Discrimination cases also allow jury trials, unlike many employment disputes.

${state} juries are particularly sympathetic to discrimination victims, especially in age, race, and disability cases. Discrimination claims require showing your protected characteristic was a motivating factor in termination. Evidence includes discriminatory comments, disparate treatment, statistical evidence, or temporal proximity between protected activity and termination.

In ${state}, discrimination cases routinely settle for substantially more than pure contract claims because employers face jury exposure and reputational harm. Discrimination also supports higher emotional distress damages recognizing the psychological impact of being fired for illegal reasons. Attorney fees awarded to prevailing discrimination plaintiffs can exceed damages themselves, creating additional leverage. Document any comments, patterns, or evidence suggesting discriminatory motive to maximize your ${state} wrongful termination recovery.`
  },

  lost_benefits: {
    title: "Lost Benefits Add Substantial Hidden Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Lost employment benefits represent significant economic damages beyond lost wages that many employees overlook. In ${state}, comprehensive benefits packages—health insurance, retirement contributions, stock options, life insurance, and other perks—often represent 20-40% of total compensation. When you're wrongfully terminated, you lose not just your paycheck but this entire benefits package, substantially increasing your economic damages.

Lost benefits affect ${state} wrongful termination cases significantly. Health insurance loss is particularly impactful—COBRA coverage is expensive, and the value of employer-provided insurance can be $500-$2,000+ monthly for families. Retirement contributions include not just your 401(k) deferrals but employer matching and pension accruals. Stock options or equity compensation that would have vested represent substantial value, especially in growing companies.

Life and disability insurance, tuition reimbursement, vehicle allowances, expense accounts, and paid time off all have monetary value. In ${state}, lost benefits are calculated by determining the employer's cost for each benefit and multiplying by months of unemployment or front pay period. Benefits also project into front pay calculations—if you'll never recover equivalent benefits, that loss continues into the future.

Document your complete benefits package: enrollment materials, benefits statements, and HR documents showing full compensation value. Many ${state} wrongful termination settlements significantly undervalue benefits, so carefully calculating benefits losses ensures you recover full economic damages. Benefits can add tens or hundreds of thousands to your case value.`
  },

  claim_filed_date: {
    title: "When You Filed Your Insurance Claim",
    getContent: (state) => `The date you initially filed your insurance claim is essential for calculating damages in ${state} bad faith cases. This date establishes when the insurance company's duty to promptly investigate and pay began. The time between filing and denial or payment determines whether delays were unreasonable—a key element of bad faith claims. In ${state}, insurance companies must acknowledge claims within specific timeframes and investigate promptly, with violations supporting bad faith findings and additional damages beyond policy benefits.`
  },

  claim_denied_date: {
    title: "When Your Claim Was Denied",
    getContent: (state) => `The denial date marks when the insurance company formally refused your claim in ${state}. This date is critical for calculating how long benefits were wrongfully withheld and determines the period for which you're entitled to back-payment of benefits. The time between filing and denial also reveals whether the insurer conducted a thorough investigation or rushed to deny your claim. In ${state}, unreasonably quick denials or extended delays before denial both support bad faith claims and increase damages.`
  },

  still_unable_to_work: {
    title: "Continuing Disability Affects Future Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Whether you remain unable to work due to disability is crucial for determining ongoing and future damages in ${state}. If you're still disabled and unable to work, your claim includes not just past denied benefits but also future benefits you'll continue losing. This dramatically increases case value, as permanent disability creates a stream of damages extending years into the future. In ${state}, courts calculate present value of future benefits based on your life expectancy and benefit amount, potentially adding hundreds of thousands to case value.`
  },

  found_new_job: {
    title: "New Employment After Termination",
    getContent: (state) => `Whether you found new employment after wrongful termination is critical to calculating economic damages in ${state}. If you remain unemployed, you continue accruing back pay damages from termination until trial or settlement. If you found new work, the law requires calculating mitigation—the new salary reduces (but doesn't eliminate) your ongoing damages. This question helps determine the scope of your economic losses and demonstrates your good-faith efforts to mitigate damages.

In ${state}, wrongful termination damages include the period from termination until you find comparable employment. If you've been unemployed since termination, damages accumulate monthly based on your prior salary and benefits. However, if you found a new position—even at lower pay—${state} law credits the new income against your damages while still compensating you for the salary difference.

Finding new employment doesn't eliminate your claim. If your new salary is lower than your previous compensation, you're still entitled to the difference (sometimes called "front pay") for a reasonable period. In ${state}, courts consider factors like your age, skills, and local job market when determining how long salary differential damages should continue. Document your job search efforts thoroughly to show you actively sought to mitigate damages.`
  },

  new_annual_salary: {
    title: "New Position Salary Affects Damage Mitigation",
    getContent: (state) => `Your new annual salary is essential for calculating damage mitigation in ${state} wrongful termination cases. When you find new employment after wrongful termination, the law requires reducing your damages by the new income—but you're still entitled to compensation for the salary difference if your new position pays less. This ensures you're made whole while acknowledging your efforts to mitigate damages.

In ${state}, if your previous salary was $80,000 and your new salary is $60,000, you're entitled to the $20,000 annual difference for a period determined by factors like your age, industry, and job market conditions. Courts recognize that wrongful termination often forces workers into lower-paying positions, and ${state} law compensates for this economic harm.

New salary also helps establish the reasonableness of your job search. Taking a significantly lower salary demonstrates the difficulty you faced finding comparable work and may support longer front pay awards. Conversely, finding equal or better compensation quickly might reduce damages but doesn't eliminate claims for emotional distress, reputational harm, or punitive damages if discrimination or retaliation occurred.`
  },

  months_unpaid: {
    title: "Unpaid Wages Period",
    getContent: (state) => `This field captures the number of months wages went unpaid in ${state}. Wage theft claims calculate damages based on the duration of non-payment, with each month of unpaid wages adding to your total recovery. The longer wages remain unpaid, the greater your damages—including potential liquidated damages that can double your recovery and interest that accrues from the date wages were due. ${state} wage laws provide strong protections for workers, with penalties and damages that increase based on the duration and severity of wage violations.`
  },

  num_employees_affected: {
    title: "Multiple Affected Employees Create Class Action Potential",
    getContent: (state) => `When an employer's unlawful practices affect multiple employees, it transforms individual claims into potential class or collective actions with dramatically increased exposure. In ${state}, systemic violations affecting 10, 50, or hundreds of workers create massive aggregate damages that force employers to settle for substantial amounts or face devastating verdicts. The number of affected employees is crucial to case valuation and litigation strategy.

Number of affected employees impacts ${state} employment cases fundamentally. Individual wage theft of $5,000 seems modest, but multiply by 100 affected employees and exposure reaches $500,000 before penalties, interest, and attorney fees. Class actions also invoke multiplier statutes—many ${state} wage laws provide double or triple damages, rapidly escalating exposure.

Pattern evidence from multiple employees proving systematic violations eliminates employer defenses that individual claims were isolated mistakes. In ${state}, federal collective actions under FLSA or state class actions become viable with sufficient affected employees, though requirements vary. More affected employees also means more witness testimony, more documentary evidence, and overwhelming proof of the violation pattern.

Insurance companies and employers understand that systemic claims have catastrophic exposure and typically settle quickly to contain damages. Number of affected employees also affects public policy—${state} attorneys general and regulatory agencies may intervene in widespread violations. Calculate total exposure across all employees to demonstrate the scope of violations and pressure settlement. In ${state}, cases affecting multiple employees routinely settle for 10-100 times individual case values.`
  },

  time_records: {
    title: "Time Records Prove Wage Theft Claims",
    getContent: (state) => `Having contemporaneous time records—timesheets, punch cards, time clocks, or personal logs—provides powerful documentary evidence that proves wage theft claims. In ${state}, time records eliminate the credibility contest inherent in many wage disputes by showing exactly when you worked. Employers struggle to dispute records showing unpaid hours, making settlements faster and larger when you have strong documentation.

Time records affect ${state} wage cases dramatically. Official employer time records showing unpaid hours prove your case conclusively. When employers lack or destroyed records, ${state} law may shift the burden to employers to disprove your reasonable estimates of hours worked.

Personal contemporaneous logs—noting start/stop times, breaks, and duties—carry substantial weight when official records are absent. Text messages, emails, or other communications about work hours corroborate time records. GPS data, building entry logs, computer login times, or security footage can verify hours worked.

In ${state}, the Federal Labor Standards Act and state wage laws require employers to maintain accurate time records, and failure to do so benefits employees in litigation. Time records also prove patterns: systematic clock-out requirements while continuing work, automatic deductions for breaks not taken, or off-the-clock work requirements. These patterns transform isolated incidents into systematic violations warranting higher damages and penalties.

In ${state}, cases with strong time records settle quickly because employers know they can't dispute documented evidence. Always maintain personal time records, especially if you suspect wage violations.`
  },

  misclassified: {
    title: "Employee Misclassification Enables Massive Wage Claims",
    getContent: (state) => `Employee misclassification—improperly categorizing workers as independent contractors or exempt employees—enables employers to avoid paying overtime, payroll taxes, and benefits they legally owe. In ${state}, misclassification violations often affect multiple workers and accumulate massive unpaid wage claims over months or years. Misclassification cases frequently become class actions with substantial exposure.

Misclassification affects ${state} wage cases powerfully. Workers misclassified as independent contractors are owed overtime pay, unemployment insurance, workers' compensation, and employment law protections they were denied. Employees misclassified as exempt from overtime are owed time-and-a-half for all hours over 40 weekly.

These violations compound rapidly—a worker owed 10 hours weekly overtime at $25/hour accumulates $13,000 annually in unpaid overtime. Over several years across multiple employees, exposure reaches hundreds of thousands or millions. ${state} law provides strict tests for independent contractor and exempt status based on control, duties, and compensation.

Misclassification is often systemic—employers misclassify entire categories of workers. In ${state}, misclassification cases commonly become class actions because the same illegal policy affects all workers in that classification. Penalties and liquidated damages double or triple actual wages owed.

Attorney fees add substantial exposure. Misclassification also creates tax liability for employers. Document how you were classified, your actual duties, hours worked, and control exercised over your work. In ${state}, misclassification cases routinely result in six or seven-figure settlements when multiple workers are affected.`
  },

  individual_damages: {
    title: "Individual Damages Determine Class Member Recovery",
    getContent: (state) => `Your individual damages in a class action determine your personal recovery from any settlement or verdict. In ${state}, class actions aggregate many small individual harms into large collective damages, but each class member's recovery depends on their specific losses. Understanding your individual damages helps evaluate whether joining a class action is worthwhile compared to pursuing an individual claim.

Individual damages affect ${state} class actions in multiple ways. Your recovery equals your proportional share of the settlement or verdict based on your specific damages. If the class settles for $10 million and your individual damages represent 0.1% of total class damages, you'd receive approximately $10,000.

Some class actions use claims processes where members submit evidence of their specific damages to receive larger individual payments. Others divide settlements equally among class members or use formulas based on transaction amounts or injury severity.

In ${state}, class members must decide whether participating in the class action provides better recovery than individual litigation. Small individual damages (under $10,000) typically favor class participation, as individual litigation isn't economically viable. Large individual damages (over $100,000) may warrant opting out and pursuing individual claims for full recovery.

Class action participation also eliminates litigation costs and risks. Calculate your individual damages carefully: document purchases, transactions, losses, or injuries specifically affecting you. This determines whether the class action adequately compensates your harm or whether individual litigation is better for your situation in ${state}.`
  },

  num_class_members: {
    title: "Class Size Determines Total Case Exposure",
    getContent: (state) => `The number of class members dramatically affects class action valuations because it determines total aggregate exposure. In ${state}, class actions involving hundreds or thousands of members create massive potential damages even when individual harms are modest. The class size is crucial for class certification, settlement negotiations, and ultimate recovery amounts.

Number of class members affects ${state} class actions fundamentally. Large classes create enormous exposure—if 10,000 consumers each lost $500, aggregate damages reach $5 million before trebling, penalties, or attorney fees. This exposure forces defendants to settle rather than risk trial.

Class size also affects class certification: ${state} courts require that classes be so numerous that joinder of all members is impractical, typically meaning 40+ members. Larger classes strengthen certification because individual litigation is obviously impractical. In settlement negotiations, total class size determines total settlement value even if per-member recovery seems modest.

Notification costs also increase with class size—locating and notifying thousands of members is expensive, affecting net settlement value. Large classes attract more capable plaintiffs' attorneys due to higher potential fees. However, very large classes may reduce per-member recovery as the settlement amount is divided among more people.

In ${state}, class action settlements often range from 5-30% of total theoretical damages depending on case strength, so a class with $100 million exposure might settle for $10-20 million. Class size estimation is critical for evaluating case value and settlement fairness in ${state} class litigation.`
  },

  duration_of_harm: {
    title: "Harm Duration Multiplies Class Action Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `The duration of harmful conduct—how many months or years the defendant's violations continued—directly multiplies total class action damages. In ${state}, longer violation periods mean more affected transactions, more class members, and higher aggregate damages. Duration also proves pattern and intent, strengthening liability and supporting punitive damages.

Harm duration affects ${state} class actions substantially. Violations continuing for years accumulate massive damages as they affect more consumers over time. A data breach is a single event, but systematic consumer fraud or employment violations compound monthly or annually. Each additional month adds more victims, more violations, and more damages.

In ${state}, duration also proves the systematic nature of violations—isolated mistakes don't continue for years, but deliberate illegal practices do. This supports punitive damages by showing the defendant persisted despite knowing about violations. Duration affects statute of limitations issues: some damages may be time-barred if violations began too long ago, while recent violations remain actionable.

In ${state}, longer duration violations also mean more documentary evidence, more witnesses, and stronger proof of pattern. Settlement negotiations focus heavily on duration because it directly multiplies exposure. Defendants argue for shorter durations to limit damages, while plaintiffs seek to extend the violation period.

Expert testimony about when violations began and ended becomes crucial. In ${state}, accurately establishing the full duration of harmful conduct ensures maximum aggregate damages and the largest possible class recovery.`
  },

  duration_of_violation: {
    title: "Duration of Violation",
    getContent: (state) => `In civil rights violations, the duration of discriminatory conduct or rights violation is crucial to calculating damages. This field captures how many months the unlawful conduct continued in ${state}. Longer violations typically result in higher damage awards, as extended discrimination or rights violations cause greater harm and demonstrate more egregious conduct. The duration also affects statutes of limitations in ${state}, as some violations may be continuing wrongs while others have specific time limits for filing claims.`
  },

  documented_evidence: {
    title: "Documentary Evidence Strengthens Class Certification",
    getContent: (state) => `Having strong documentary evidence—written policies, emails, contracts, transaction records, or internal communications—dramatically strengthens class action cases. In ${state}, documentary evidence proves systematic violations affecting all class members, supports class certification, and increases settlement values. Documents show the defendant's own records establishing liability, eliminating credibility battles.

Documentary evidence affects ${state} class actions powerfully. Written policies implementing illegal practices prove systematic violations affecting all class members uniformly. Emails or internal communications showing defendants knew about violations support punitive damages. Transaction records document each violation across thousands of transactions.

Contracts with illegal terms affect all consumers who signed them. In ${state}, documentary evidence is essential for class certification because it shows common questions of law and fact affecting all class members. Without documents, defendants argue each case requires individualized proof, defeating class treatment.

Documents also expedite litigation—undeniable written evidence leads to faster settlements as defendants can't dispute their own records. Consumer protection and wage class actions particularly benefit from employer records, contracts, policies, and transaction data.

In ${state}, obtain documents through discovery, whistleblowers, or public records requests. Internal emails showing awareness of problems or decisions to violate laws are especially valuable. Preserve all documents you possess and identify key documents in the defendant's possession. Strong documentary evidence can increase ${state} class action settlement values by 50-200% by eliminating liability disputes and proving systematic violations across the entire class.`
  },

  pattern_of_conduct: {
    title: "Pattern of Conduct Proves Systematic Violations",
    getContent: (state) => `Demonstrating a pattern of illegal conduct—not isolated incidents but systematic repeated violations—transforms your case by proving intentional wrongdoing warranting punitive damages. In ${state}, patterns eliminate defenses that violations were mistakes or isolated events. Pattern evidence shows the defendant deliberately engaged in illegal practices, dramatically increasing case value and settlement leverage.

Pattern of conduct affects ${state} cases across multiple claim types. Employment discrimination patterns—repeatedly firing older workers, paying women less, or denying promotions to minorities—prove systematic discrimination warranting higher damages. Civil rights violations showing repeated excessive force or false arrests demonstrate policy deficiencies supporting municipal liability.

Consumer fraud patterns affecting thousands of consumers prove intentional deceptive practices. Insurance bad faith patterns of denying similar claims show company-wide policies rather than isolated adjuster mistakes. In ${state}, pattern evidence supports punitive damages by proving willful or reckless conduct.

Patterns also prove causation: if the defendant repeatedly engaged in the same violation, your claim wasn't coincidental but part of the pattern. Pattern evidence includes testimony from other victims, statistical analysis showing systematic disparities, expert testimony about practices, and documentary evidence of repeated violations.

${state} courts allow pattern evidence to prove intent and punitive damages even if each instance seems modest individually. Pattern evidence also attracts regulatory attention and public pressure. In ${state}, proving patterns rather than isolated incidents can multiply case values three to ten times through punitive damages, heightened emotional distress awards, and increased settlement pressure.`
  },

  regulatory_violations: {
    title: "Regulatory Violations Add Statutory Penalties",
    getContent: (state) => `Violations of federal or state regulations—safety rules, consumer protection laws, labor standards, or industry-specific regulations—add statutory penalties, liquidated damages, and attorney fees beyond common law damages. In ${state}, regulatory violations create strict liability and predetermined penalty amounts that multiply case values. Violations of written regulations also eliminate many defenses.

Regulatory violations affect ${state} cases dramatically. Many regulations provide statutory penalties per violation—consumer protection laws often impose $500-$10,000 per violation, wage laws provide double or triple damages, and safety violations carry civil penalties. These stack with actual damages: if you lost $50,000 plus statutory penalties of $100,000, total recovery reaches $150,000.

In ${state}, regulatory violations also typically provide attorney fee recovery, making cases economically viable even with modest individual damages. Violations of written regulations prove negligence per se or strict liability—if regulations required specific safety measures and the defendant didn't comply, liability is established. This eliminates the defendant's ability to argue they met standards of care.

Regulatory violations also attract government enforcement: OSHA, EPA, DOL, FTC, and state agencies may investigate, imposing additional penalties and creating public pressure. In ${state}, some regulations allow whistleblower qui tam actions where you can sue on the government's behalf for a percentage of recovery.

Document specific regulations violated, violation evidence, and applicable penalties. Expert testimony about industry regulations and defendant's compliance failures strengthens claims. In ${state}, regulatory violations commonly double or triple total case values by adding statutory penalties to compensatory damages.`
  },

  claim_amount: {
    title: "Claim Amount Determines Bad Faith Exposure",
    getContent: (state) => `The dollar amount of your insurance claim fundamentally determines the stakes in bad faith cases. In ${state}, higher claim amounts create greater bad faith exposure because the damages from delayed or denied payment are proportionally larger. A denied $500,000 claim causes vastly more financial hardship than a denied $5,000 claim, affecting both compensatory damages and potential punitive damages.

Claim amount affects ${state} insurance bad faith cases substantially. Your underlying claim value sets the baseline damages from denial or delay. If your valid $300,000 claim is wrongfully denied, your damages start at $300,000 plus interest, emotional distress, consequential damages, and attorney fees.

Large claim denials cause severe financial hardship: inability to pay medical bills, risk of home foreclosure, or business failure. These consequences support higher emotional distress damages and punitive damages. In ${state}, punitive damages often relate to compensatory damages and claim amounts—larger claims support larger punitive awards.

Claim amount also affects settlement leverage: insurers know bad faith on large claims exposes them to catastrophic verdicts, making them more willing to settle. Claims exceeding policy limits create particular pressure, as bad faith findings can impose extra-contractual liability exceeding coverage.

In ${state}, document all financial hardship caused by claim denial: missed medical treatments, collection notices, credit damage, loan denials, or business losses. The claim amount determines the financial impact and thus total recoverable damages. Bad faith cases involving large claims routinely result in multi-million dollar verdicts in ${state} when juries see how claim denial devastated your finances and wellbeing.`
  },

  policy_limits: {
    title: "Policy Limits Cap Primary Recovery",
    getContent: (state) => `Insurance policy limits represent the maximum amount the insurance company must pay for covered claims. In ${state}, policy limits fundamentally constrain your recovery from the insurer, though you may pursue additional sources. Understanding policy limits is crucial for realistic case valuation and determining whether bad faith or excess liability claims are necessary to achieve full compensation.

Policy limits affect ${state} insurance cases in multiple ways. Standard auto policies often have limits like $100,000 per person, meaning you can't recover more than $100,000 from that policy even if your damages exceed it. When your damages clearly exceed policy limits, settlement negotiations focus on securing the full limits quickly.

In ${state}, insurers who unreasonably refuse to settle within limits when damages exceed them face bad faith claims for the excess. This creates powerful leverage: if your damages are $500,000 but policy limits are $100,000, the insurer's failure to tender limits exposes them to the full $500,000 plus punitive damages.

Policy limits also guide litigation strategy—when limits are insufficient, you may need to pursue the defendant's personal assets, umbrella policies, or your own underinsured motorist coverage. In ${state}, some policies allow stacking multiple coverages to increase total limits. Higher policy limits mean your case has room to reach full value without exceeding available coverage.

Document all applicable policies: defendant's primary policy, umbrella or excess policies, and your UIM coverage. Understanding total available policy limits helps determine whether negotiation or litigation best achieves maximum recovery in ${state}.`
  },

  claim_denied: {
    title: "Claim Denial Is Foundation of Bad Faith Cases",
    getContent: (state) => `An outright insurance claim denial—as opposed to delayed payment or underpayment—represents the most serious insurer misconduct and forms the basis of bad faith claims. In ${state}, when an insurer denies a valid claim without reasonable basis, they breach their duty of good faith and fair dealing, exposing themselves to extra-contractual damages including emotional distress, consequential damages, punitive damages, and attorney fees.

Claim denial affects ${state} insurance cases fundamentally. Denials cause immediate and severe harm: you're left without expected benefits at the moment of greatest need. Wrongful denials force you to pay medical bills, living expenses, or property repairs yourself, creating financial hardship.

In ${state}, claim denials support bad faith claims when the insurer lacked reasonable basis for denial or failed to adequately investigate. Outright denials are more egregious than mere delays or low settlements, supporting higher damages. Claim denial often forces you to hire attorneys and file lawsuits to obtain benefits you were entitled to from the beginning, creating attorney fees the insurer should pay.

In ${state}, wrongful claim denials support emotional distress damages: anxiety, depression, financial stress, and feeling betrayed by your insurer during crisis. If the denial was particularly unreasonable or based on flimsy pretexts, punitive damages may apply.

Document the denial carefully: save denial letters, note the reasons given, and preserve evidence proving the claim was valid. Challenge denials promptly through internal appeals while preserving your right to sue. In ${state}, wrongful claim denials can result in damages several times the claim amount when bad faith is proven.`
  },

  written_denials: {
    title: "Written Denials Provide Evidence of Bad Faith",
    getContent: (state) => `Having written denial letters from your insurance company provides crucial documentary evidence for bad faith claims. In ${state}, written denials preserve the insurer's exact justifications, reveal shifting explanations, and often contain admissions or unreasonable positions that prove bad faith. Written denials eliminate the insurer's ability to claim miscommunication or misunderstanding, creating powerful evidence.

Written denials affect ${state} insurance bad faith cases significantly. Denial letters show exactly what reasons the insurer gave for denial, allowing you to prove those reasons were pretextual or unreasonable. When insurers give different reasons across multiple denials, written letters expose the inconsistencies, suggesting they're grasping for any excuse rather than honestly evaluating your claim.

Written denials also preserve crucial facts: dates of denial, who made decisions, what evidence they ignored, and what policy provisions they misinterpreted. In ${state}, vague or conclusory written denials that don't adequately explain the basis for denial support bad faith claims, as insurers must reasonably investigate and communicate.

Written denials that cite policy exclusions that don't apply, ignore favorable evidence, or mischaracterize facts demonstrate bad faith. Compare written denial letters to policy language, medical records, and other evidence to prove the denial was unreasonable.

Consult experts who can testify that the insurer's written rationale doesn't withstand scrutiny. In ${state}, written denials serve as the insurer's own admission of their reasoning, which you can then demolish through expert testimony, showing their decision was unreasonable and in bad faith.`
  },

  monthly_benefit: {
    title: "Monthly Benefit Amount Determines Disability Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Your monthly disability benefit amount establishes the baseline for calculating damages in denied or delayed disability claims. In ${state}, the monthly benefit multiplied by the number of months benefits were wrongfully withheld equals your economic damages before adding interest, attorney fees, and any bad faith damages. Higher monthly benefits create proportionally higher damages from benefit denials.

Monthly benefit affects ${state} disability cases directly. If your disability policy provides $5,000 monthly and benefits were denied for 24 months, your economic damages total $120,000 plus interest. Benefits of $10,000 monthly would create $240,000 in damages over the same period.

In ${state}, monthly benefits continue accumulating damages until the insurer pays or your eligibility ends, creating ongoing exposure for insurers. This pressure often forces settlement as damages mount monthly. Monthly benefit amounts also affect emotional distress damages—losing $10,000 monthly causes greater financial hardship than losing $2,000 monthly, supporting higher non-economic damages.

In ${state}, disability bad faith cases often award several times the monthly benefit amount in emotional distress damages recognizing the devastating impact of losing income while disabled. Monthly benefits also project into the future: if you remain permanently disabled, future benefit payments for years or decades may be at stake, creating substantial exposure.

Document your monthly benefit amount precisely using your policy, benefit statements, and payment history before benefits stopped. In ${state}, the monthly benefit amount is the single most important factor determining total disability claim damages.`
  },

  medical_evidence: {
    title: "Strong Medical Evidence Proves Disability Claims",
    getContent: (state) => `Having comprehensive medical evidence—physician reports, diagnostic tests, functional capacity evaluations, and expert opinions—is essential to proving disability claims. In ${state}, disability insurers deny claims citing insufficient medical evidence, making strong documentation crucial to overcoming denials. Compelling medical evidence not only establishes your disability but also proves the insurer's denial was unreasonable, supporting bad faith claims.

Medical evidence affects ${state} disability cases fundamentally. Your treating physicians' opinions carry substantial weight—if doctors state you cannot work, insurers struggle to justify denial. Objective medical tests (MRIs, X-rays, nerve studies) provide irrefutable evidence of physical impairments. Functional capacity evaluations objectively measure your physical limitations and work capacity.

Neuropsychological testing documents cognitive impairments. In ${state}, the more comprehensive and consistent your medical evidence, the more unreasonable the insurer's denial appears. Medical evidence that clearly satisfies the policy's disability definition makes bad faith obvious. Conversely, insurers exploit gaps in medical evidence to deny claims.

Obtain regular medical treatment documenting your conditions and limitations. Ask doctors to complete forms detailing how your impairments prevent work. Obtain independent medical evaluations if insurers use their own doctors to deny claims.

In ${state}, strong medical evidence increases settlement values by proving both that you're disabled and that the insurer acted unreasonably in denying your well-documented claim. Cases with compelling medical evidence routinely settle for full benefits plus bad faith damages because insurers know they'll lose at trial.`
  },

  unable_work: {
    title: "Complete Work Inability Maximizes Disability Benefits",
    getContent: (state) => `Being completely unable to work—as opposed to partially disabled or able to work with restrictions—typically entitles you to the highest disability benefits and strongest disability claims. In ${state}, "total disability" policies provide full benefits when you cannot perform any substantial gainful activity or your own occupation (depending on policy definition). Complete work inability makes denial of benefits particularly unreasonable and supports larger bad faith damages.

Inability to work affects ${state} disability cases substantially. Total disability claims are stronger than partial disability claims because they meet the strictest policy definitions. If you literally cannot work at all due to physical or mental impairments, the insurer's basis for denial is extremely limited.

In ${state}, total disability is typically proven through comprehensive medical evidence showing severe limitations across all functional capacities. Vocational experts may testify that no work exists within your restrictions. When insurers deny total disability claims despite compelling evidence you cannot work, bad faith becomes obvious—they're refusing benefits to someone who clearly satisfies policy terms.

Complete work inability also means you have no income to offset damages: every month without benefits leaves you with zero income, creating severe financial hardship that supports emotional distress damages.

In ${state}, document how your conditions prevent all work: specific limitations from doctors, failed work attempts, vocational expert opinions, and the impact of having no income. Total disability cases have highest settlement values because the insurer's liability is clearest and the financial impact on you is most severe. Insurers pay more to resolve claims where denial is indefensible.`
  },

  financial_loss: {
    title: "Total Financial Loss Determines Professional Malpractice Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Your total financial loss directly determines economic damages in professional malpractice cases. In ${state}, when a professional's negligence causes monetary losses—failed investments, tax penalties, lost business opportunities, or adverse legal outcomes—you're entitled to compensation for all financial harm. Accurately calculating total financial loss is crucial to maximizing malpractice recovery.

Financial loss affects ${state} professional malpractice valuations fundamentally. Economic damages equal the difference between your financial position but for the malpractice and your actual position after the malpractice. Attorney malpractice: if your attorney's error cost you a $500,000 lawsuit recovery, your damages are $500,000. Accountant malpractice: if accounting errors resulted in $200,000 in tax penalties and interest, that's your financial loss.

Financial advisor malpractice: the difference between what your investments should have returned and actual returns. In ${state}, financial loss calculations often require expert testimony—damages experts, forensic accountants, or vocational experts—to establish precisely what you lost due to the malpractice.

Some losses are obvious (tax penalties paid), while others require economic modeling (lost business income from professional's errors). Include all financial impacts: direct losses, consequential damages, lost opportunities, and costs incurred fixing the professional's mistakes.

In ${state}, professional malpractice cases involving large financial losses can reach millions in damages. Document your financial loss comprehensively: tax records, financial statements, investment statements, and expert analyses proving causation between the professional's negligence and your monetary losses.`
  },

  business_revenue_lost: {
    title: "Lost Business Revenue Adds Substantial Malpractice Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `When professional malpractice causes your business to lose revenue—through operational disruptions, lost opportunities, contract breaches, or damaged reputation—these losses add substantially to economic damages. In ${state}, business revenue losses can exceed direct professional fees by orders of magnitude, particularly when professional errors affect ongoing business operations or major transactions.

Business revenue lost affects ${state} professional malpractice cases dramatically. A CPA's error causing an audit and business shutdown might cost hundreds of thousands in lost revenue beyond the accounting fees paid. An attorney's failure to file trademark protection might allow competitors to capture market share, costing millions. An architect's design flaw might delay construction and cost rental income.

In ${state}, business revenue losses require expert testimony to establish causation and calculate damages. You must prove the professional's negligence directly caused the revenue loss and quantify what revenue you would have earned but for the negligence. This often involves financial experts analyzing historical revenue, industry trends, and projected growth.

Business revenue losses also compound: a single error might cause ongoing reduced revenues for months or years. In ${state}, document revenue losses meticulously: financial statements, tax returns, sales records, contracts lost, and business valuations showing impact.

Obtain expert analysis proving causation between professional errors and revenue decline. Business revenue losses can transform modest malpractice cases into major recoveries when the professional's mistakes severely harmed business operations or growth. In ${state}, these cases often settle for several times the professional fees paid, reflecting the business impact.`
  },

  written_agreement: {
    title: "Written Agreements Establish Professional Duties",
    getContent: (state) => `Having a written agreement with your professional—engagement letter, contract, or retainer agreement—provides crucial evidence establishing what duties the professional owed you. In ${state}, written agreements eliminate disputes about scope of work, professional obligations, and standards of care. Clear contractual duties make proving breach of duty easier and strengthen malpractice claims.

Written agreements affect ${state} professional malpractice cases substantially. Contracts specify exactly what services the professional agreed to provide, deadlines they agreed to meet, and standards they agreed to follow. When professionals breach these written obligations, liability is clear.

Written agreements also establish the professional relationship necessary for malpractice claims—proving you had attorney-client, accountant-client, or other professional relationships. In ${state}, written fee agreements show you paid for professional services and relied on their expertise. Engagement letters often incorporate professional standards or specify outcomes, making breach obvious when professionals fail to deliver.

Written agreements also preserve contemporaneous evidence of your understanding and the professional's promises. When disputes arise, written contracts control over later claims of misunderstanding. In ${state}, cases with written agreements specifying duties proceed more smoothly through litigation because the duty element is established by contract.

Professionals cannot claim you misunderstood their role or that they never agreed to certain obligations. Preserve all written agreements, engagement letters, retainer agreements, proposals, and contract documents. These documents establish the professional's duties and prove breach when they failed to perform as promised. Written agreements typically increase ${state} professional malpractice case values by making liability clearer and reducing defense options.`
  },

  clear_negligence: {
    title: "Obvious Negligence Strengthens Professional Malpractice Cases",
    getContent: (state) => `When professional negligence is clear and obvious—missed deadlines causing statute of limitations, arithmetic errors in financial statements, or design flaws violating building codes—cases are much stronger and more valuable. In ${state}, clear negligence eliminates the professional's ability to claim judgment calls or reasonable disagreement among professionals. Obvious mistakes create powerful jury appeal and settlement leverage.

Clear negligence affects ${state} professional malpractice valuations substantially. Obvious errors like missing lawsuit filing deadlines, failing to file tax returns, or ignoring known building code requirements prove negligence without complex expert battles. Jurors understand these mistakes and react with sympathy for victims and frustration with negligent professionals.

In ${state}, clear negligence cases settle faster and for more money because professionals and their insurers know the mistakes are indefensible. Clear errors also support larger damages—particularly egregious negligence suggests punitive damages in some cases. When negligence is obvious, settlement negotiations focus on damages rather than liability.

This allows you to pursue full compensation without risk of losing on liability. Clear negligence also affects expert witness costs: while you still need experts to testify about standards of care, the testimony is straightforward rather than complex.

In ${state}, document exactly how the professional's conduct fell below standards. Obtain competing professionals' opinions about how obvious the error was. Highlight violations of clear rules, missed deadlines, or mistakes any professional would recognize. Cases with clear, indefensible negligence routinely settle for maximum value because professionals can't justify their errors.`
  },

  government_entity: {
    title: "Government Defendants Face Different Liability Rules",
    getContent: (state) => `When a government entity or official is the defendant—police departments, public schools, government agencies, or municipalities—different legal rules apply than private defendant cases. In ${state}, sovereign immunity, special notice requirements, damage caps, and federal civil rights laws create a unique litigation landscape. Understanding these differences is crucial for properly pursuing government liability claims.

Government entity involvement affects ${state} cases in multiple ways. Sovereign immunity may bar certain claims unless specific exceptions apply. Many states and the federal government require strict notice procedures: filing administrative claims within 30-180 days before you can sue. Failure to follow notice requirements can bar your case entirely.

In ${state}, government liability may require proving policies or customs, not just individual official conduct. Federal civil rights claims under § 1983 apply to state and local governments but not federal officials (who face Bivens claims instead). Government defendants may face damage caps limiting recovery.

However, government liability also provides advantages: deeper pockets than individual defendants, less sympathetic than private parties to juries, and inability to claim bankruptcy. § 1983 claims allow attorney fee recovery, making cases economically viable. Government transparency laws provide document access.

Qualified immunity protects some officials from individual liability but doesn't prevent suing the government entity itself. In ${state}, government cases require specialized knowledge of sovereign immunity, notice requirements, and constitutional claims. These cases often settle substantially because governments face public accountability and political pressure beyond private defendants.`
  },

  economic_damages: {
    title: "Economic Damages Form the Foundation of Civil Rights Cases",
    getContent: (state) => `Economic damages—lost wages, medical expenses, property loss, and out-of-pocket costs—resulting from civil rights violations form the baseline of compensatory damages. In ${state}, documenting your economic losses is essential to recovery, though civil rights cases also allow substantial non-economic damages for constitutional violations. Economic damages provide concrete, calculable harm that supports larger overall damage awards.

Economic damages affect ${state} civil rights cases significantly. Lost wages from wrongful arrest, suspension, or termination directly result from rights violations. Medical expenses treating injuries from excessive force are compensable. Property damage from illegal searches must be repaid.

In ${state} civil rights litigation, economic damages are relatively straightforward to prove: present pay stubs showing lost income, medical bills, and receipts. Economic losses also support larger non-economic damages—if violations caused $50,000 in economic harm, non-economic damages for pain, suffering, and emotional distress often exceed that amount.

Federal civil rights laws have no damage caps, meaning economic losses can support full compensation. Large economic damages particularly affect settlement negotiations, as they establish a minimum value even before considering non-economic and punitive damages.

In ${state}, document all economic impacts: income losses, medical and therapy costs, property damage, legal fees to clear your record, and any other out-of-pocket expenses caused by the constitutional violation. Obtain expert testimony about future economic losses if violations have ongoing financial impact. Economic damages combined with non-economic and sometimes punitive damages make civil rights cases potentially very valuable in ${state}.`
  },

  revenue_lost: {
    title: "Lost Revenue Determines IP Infringement Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Revenue you lost due to intellectual property infringement—sales you would have made but for the infringement—represents one of two primary damage measures in IP cases. In ${state}, you can recover either your lost profits or the infringer's profits (whichever is greater in trademark cases, or potentially both in patent cases). Accurately calculating lost revenue is crucial to maximizing IP infringement recovery.

Revenue lost affects ${state} IP infringement valuations fundamentally. Lost revenue damages require proving: (1) demand for your IP product, (2) you could have supplied the demand, (3) the infringer's sales were at your expense, and (4) the amount of profit you lost. This calculation often requires expert economic testimony.

Lost revenue includes not just direct sales losses but also price erosion—if infringement forced you to lower prices to compete, that's compensable. Lost market share, damaged reputation, and future sales losses may also be recoverable. In ${state}, some IP types make lost revenue easier to prove: if the infringer directly competes with you selling identical products, causation is clear.

Patent infringement, trademark infringement, and trade secret misappropriation cases commonly use lost revenue measures when you compete directly with infringers. Revenue loss calculations multiply across multiple infringing products and markets. Lost revenue also projects forward: if infringement continues or has lasting market impact, future losses add to damages.

Document your historical sales, market position, and projected revenues. Obtain expert economic analysis proving how infringement caused specific revenue losses. In ${state}, revenue lost cases can reach millions in established businesses, making this damage measure crucial to IP litigation strategy.`
  },

  infringer_profits: {
    title: "Infringer's Profits Provide Alternative IP Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `The profits the infringer earned from their unlawful use of your intellectual property represent an alternative damage measure available in IP infringement cases. In ${state}, you can recover the infringer's profits particularly when your own lost profits are difficult to calculate or when the infringer earned more than you lost. Disgorgement of infringer profits ensures they don't benefit from their wrongdoing.

Infringer profits affect ${state} IP infringement cases significantly. Once you prove the infringer's gross revenue from infringing products, the burden shifts to the infringer to prove their deductible expenses. This burden-shifting helps plaintiffs because infringers must fully document their costs or forfeit deductions. Infringer profit calculations focus on revenue directly attributable to the infringement. In patent and copyright cases, this may require apportioning profits when infringement is only one component of the product. Trademark cases often use total product profits if the mark drove sales. In ${state}, infringer profits can exceed your lost profits when the infringer operates more efficiently, reaches more customers, or makes higher margins. This damage measure also reaches downstream profits: not just manufacturing profits but distribution and retail profits too. Willful infringement can increase damages further—up to treble damages in some IP cases. Infringer profit disgorgement also sends deterrent messages: infringers can't keep their ill-gotten gains. Obtain discovery of the infringer's sales, revenues, costs, and profit margins. Expert accountants can analyze their financial records to calculate total profits. In ${state}, cases involving large infringers with substantial profits often pursue this measure to maximize recovery.`
  },

  discovery_date: {
    title: "When You Discovered the Infringement",
    getContent: (state) => `The date you discovered the intellectual property infringement is critical for statute of limitations calculations in ${state}. IP claims are typically subject to 3-6 year limitations periods that begin when you discovered or reasonably should have discovered the infringement. This date determines which infringing acts fall within the recoverable period and affects total damages. In ${state}, proving late discovery can extend the limitations period and preserve claims for older infringement.`
  },

  infringement_start_date: {
    title: "When Infringement Actually Began",
    getContent: (state) => `The date infringement actually started—when the infringer first used your IP without permission—is essential for calculating total damages in ${state}. The duration between infringement start and discovery directly multiplies damages, as each year of infringement adds more lost revenue, infringer profits, and reasonable royalty calculations. Longer infringement periods also strengthen willfulness claims if the infringer continued after notice of your rights.

In ${state}, proving infringement began years before discovery dramatically increases case value. Each additional year means more infringing sales and greater damages. For example, $100,000 annual damages over five years equals $500,000 total exposure. The infringement start date also affects willfulness findings—infringers who continue for years after you provide notice face enhanced damages that can triple your recovery in patent, trademark, and sometimes copyright cases.

Document the infringement start date through product launches, advertisements, sales records, domain registrations, or other evidence. In ${state}, you can only recover damages within the statute of limitations period (typically 3-6 years back from filing), but proving earlier infringement establishes a pattern and strengthens willfulness claims for enhanced damages.`
  },

  registered_ip: {
    title: "Registered IP Provides Stronger Remedies",
    getContent: (state) => `Having registered intellectual property—USPTO-registered patents, trademarks, or copyrights—provides significantly stronger remedies than unregistered IP rights. In ${state}, registration establishes prima facie validity, enables statutory damages, allows attorney fee recovery, and provides procedural advantages. Registered IP cases are worth substantially more than unregistered IP cases.

Registered IP affects ${state} infringement valuations dramatically. Copyright registration enables statutory damages of $750-$30,000 per work ($150,000 if willful) instead of having to prove actual damages. This transforms cases: infringement of 100 copyrighted works creates $75,000 minimum damages without proving a penny of actual loss. Patent registration is required to sue for infringement and creates presumption of validity the infringer must overcome. Trademark registration provides nationwide priority, presumed validity, and access to Trademark Trial and Appeal Board proceedings. In ${state}, registered copyrights and patents enable attorney fee awards to prevailing plaintiffs, making litigation economically viable even for modest damages. Registration also provides procedural benefits: prima facie evidence of ownership and validity that shifts burdens to infringers. Customs can seize infringing imports if your trademark or copyright is registered. Many IP licenses and sales require registered IP. In ${state}, registered IP commands higher settlements because remedies are stronger and infringer defenses are weaker. Always register valuable IP: file patent applications, register trademarks with USPTO, and register copyrights with Copyright Office. Registration typically costs hundreds to thousands but increases enforcement value by tens or hundreds of thousands through enhanced remedies.`
  },

  willful_infringement: {
    title: "Willful Infringement Enables Treble Damages",
    getContent: (state) => `Willful infringement—when the infringer knew about your intellectual property rights and intentionally infringed anyway—enables enhanced damages up to three times actual damages in most IP cases. In ${state}, proving willfulness transforms case values by adding punitive-style damages designed to punish and deter deliberate infringement. Willfulness also supports attorney fee awards.

Willful infringement affects ${state} IP cases powerfully. Patent infringement damages can be enhanced up to three times when infringement was willful. Copyright infringement allows statutory damages up to $150,000 per work (versus $30,000 for non-willful). Trademark infringement can be trebled under the Lanham Act. In ${state}, willfulness is typically proved by showing the infringer had actual notice of your IP rights—you sent cease-and-desist letters, the infringer was previously licensed, they copied your work, or they knew of your patent. Continuing infringement after receiving notice strongly suggests willfulness. Deliberate copying rather than independent creation proves willful intent. In ${state}, willfulness findings also favor attorney fee awards, adding significant pressure on infringers. Willful infringement defendants face much higher exposure and typically settle for substantially more than non-willful cases. Document all notice you provided to infringers: cease-and-desist letters, licensing offers, or conversations acknowledging your IP. Prove the infringer had access to your IP and actual knowledge of your rights. Obtain evidence showing continued infringement despite knowing it was unlawful. In ${state}, willful infringement cases routinely settle for two to three times non-willful case values due to enhanced damages exposure.`
  },

  ongoing_infringement: {
    title: "Ongoing Infringement Requires Injunctive Relief",
    getContent: (state) => `When intellectual property infringement is ongoing—the infringer continues to use your IP currently—you can seek injunctive relief ordering them to stop, in addition to monetary damages. In ${state}, injunctions provide forward-looking relief preventing future harm, while damages compensate past harm. Ongoing infringement makes injunctions appropriate and adds urgency to settlement negotiations.

Ongoing infringement affects ${state} IP cases significantly. Injunctions can be worth more than damages when infringement threatens your market position, competitive advantage, or brand identity. An injunction stopping a competitor from using your patented technology can be worth millions in preserved market share beyond past damages. Preliminary injunctions during litigation stop damage from accumulating while the case proceeds. In ${state}, injunctive relief requires proving irreparable harm that damages can't adequately compensate. Ongoing infringement typically satisfies this standard: continued market confusion (trademarks), ongoing loss of sales (patents), or continuing unauthorized copies (copyrights) cause harm that monetary damages don't fully remedy. Permanent injunctions after trial permanently prohibit infringement. In ${state}, injunction leverage often drives settlement: infringers facing injunctions that would shut down product lines settle for substantial amounts to avoid business disruption. Injunctions also provide compliance leverage and contempt power if violations continue. Document how ongoing infringement continues to harm you: current infringing sales, present market confusion, or active unauthorized copies. Prove the infringement is continuous rather than past-only. In ${state}, cases with ongoing infringement routinely secure injunctions plus damages, providing complete relief that stops both past and future harm.`
  },

  product_name: {
    title: "Product Identification Establishes Product Liability",
    getContent: (state) => `Identifying the specific product that caused your injury is essential to product liability claims. In ${state}, you must prove that a particular product was defectively designed, manufactured, or labeled and that this defect caused your injuries. Knowing the exact product name, model, manufacturer, and seller is crucial for proper identification and establishing the chain of commerce.

Product identification affects ${state} product liability cases fundamentally. You must identify the product specifically enough to show which entity designed, manufactured, and sold it. Product name helps locate the product for testing, find other similar injury reports, and identify all potential defendants in the supply chain. In ${state}, product liability can extend to manufacturers, distributors, wholesalers, and retailers. Specific product identification allows recalls to be discovered, prior complaints to be found, and design or manufacturing records to be obtained. Generic descriptions aren't sufficient—you need the brand name, model number, batch or serial numbers if possible. Product identification also helps experts analyze the defect: engineers need to examine the actual product or identical exemplars. In ${state}, keep the actual product if possible, photograph it thoroughly, preserve packaging, receipts, and manuals showing exact product identification. The product name allows researching whether it was recalled, if others were injured by the same product, and whether the manufacturer had prior notice of defects. Accurate product identification is the first step in every product liability case and essential to recovering compensation in ${state}.`
  },

  product_recalled: {
    title: "Product Recalls Prove Defects and Manufacturer Knowledge",
    getContent: (state) => `If the product that injured you was recalled—either before or after your injury—this provides powerful evidence of product defects and manufacturer knowledge of dangers. In ${state}, product recalls demonstrate the manufacturer admitted the product was unsafe, dramatically strengthening your product liability case. Recalls prove both the defect and that the manufacturer knew about it.

Product recalls affect ${state} product liability cases enormously. Recalls are the manufacturer's admission that the product has safety defects. This eliminates their ability to claim the product was safe or defects were unforeseeable. In ${state}, recalls particularly support punitive damages when manufacturers delayed recalls despite knowing about dangers. If your injury occurred after the manufacturer knew about defects but before they recalled the product, it shows they consciously disregarded consumer safety for profit. Recalls also provide documentary evidence: recall notices detail the specific defect, the danger it poses, and how many products were affected. This corroborates your experts' opinions about product defects. In ${state}, recalls affecting millions of products prove widespread defects, not isolated manufacturing anomalies. Manufacturer knowledge through recall decisions shows the defect was significant enough to warrant recall, supporting substantial damages. Recalls also generate publicity and other victim identification, potentially creating class actions or MDL consolidations with shared litigation costs. Search recall databases (CPSC, NHTSA, FDA) for your product. Document recall timing relative to your injury. Obtain recall notices and manufacturer communications about the defect. In ${state}, product recall evidence can double or triple case values by proving defect and knowledge elements conclusively.`
  }
};
